<HEADLINE> VW Confirms Continued Bid for Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Europe's largest carmaker Volkswagen
confirmed Friday that it was still bidding for British carmaker
Rolls-Royce despite Rolls' parent company Vickers has announced
its German rival BMW as the winner in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
Kurt Rippholz, spokesman for the German company, told German
press agency DPA in Wolfsburg that VW submitted an improved bid
last Monday, on which Vickers announced the principal agreement to
negotiate with BMW.
</P>
<P>
Rippholz said that along with the new offer, VW also presented
Vickers with detailed investment plans and concepts about
Rolls-Royce's future development.
</P>
<P>
Rippholz declined to disclose financial details of VW's new
offer. But German press reports estimated the bid well above the
340 million pounds (570 million U.S. dollars) offered by BMW,
which makes the V12 engine for Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
Suedeutsche newspaper said VW offered about 1.1 billion marks
(600 million dollars), while the Financial Times had earlier
reported a figure of 1.7 billion marks (927 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Vickers said that it would negotiate exclusively
with BMW during this month and a final decision would be made at a
special shareholders' meeting in late May.
</P>
<P>
BMW has threatened to cease supplying engines and components to
Rolls-Royce should it not take over the luxury carmaker.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
