<HEADLINE> UK Aircraft Carrier to Leave Gulf for Refit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Defense Ministry said
Friday that the aircraft carrier sent to the Gulf at the height of
the recent U.N. arms inspection crisis with Iraq will leave the
area for a planned refit, but denying it was reducing its military
capability in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft carrier HMS Illustrious, which carries Harrier
jets and was ordered to the Gulf in mid-January, will leave later
this month for a planned refit, and four extra Tornado aircraft
will move to the region, the Defense Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It said that the planes, which are better suited to operate in
the extreme heat of the coming summer months, will join the eight
Tornados already based in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Defense Secretary George Robertson said
Friday in a statement that it was too soon to wind down activity
in the area.
</P>
<P>
"Saddam has not yet provided the evidence we need to be sure
that he has destroyed all his weapons of mass destruction," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It is therefore too soon to relax our vigilance and reduce our
military capability in the Gulf," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
