<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Makes 24-Million-Dollar Appeal for Somali Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) presented here on Friday an
appeal of 24 million U.S. dollars for its 1998 Somali program.
</P>
<P>
"The program is in a crucial phase," said UNHCR's Regional
Director Albert-Alain Peters. "Thousands of Somali refugees have
decided to return home, mainly to the northwest of the country,
and we need to be able to give the same opportunity to many
others."
</P>
<P>
The majority of refugees who fled the civil war in Somalia
beginning in 1989 are in Ethiopia (240,000 as of January 1, 1998)
and Kenya (134,000). Smaller groups are in Djibouti, Yemen and
Libya.
</P>
<P>
Authorities in Hargeisa in northwest Somalia have agreed with
UNHCR on a cumulative target of 100,000 returns for 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR expects 60,000 Somalis from Ethiopia to return to the
northwest in 1998, and another 16,500 from other countries.
</P>
<P>
"In some areas of Somalia the situation is very encouraging,"
Peters said. "This is why people are registering to return. We
must give our full support to reintegration where people are
asking for."
</P>
<P>
"If we do so now, we have the chance to make their return a
success," Peters stressed.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR's reintegration program includes aid for education, where
in some regions less than 20 percent of primary school-aged
children attend school, and boys outnumber girls two to one.
</P>
<P>
Assistance also targets the estimated 35 percent of households
headed by women, with initiatives designed to give women their own
source of livelihood through a range of small businesses. Clean
water will be supplied to communities and their livestock from new
wells and traditional water catchments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Governor General Visits Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Rafiq Tarar
said Friday that the first-ever visit to Pakistan by Canadian
Governor General Romeo Leblanc will strengthen the bilateral ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani-Canadian relationship dates back to the time when
Pakistan became independent, said Tarar while welcoming the
Canadian governor general, who arrived here Friday on a four-day
state visit, at the Presidential House.
</P>
<P>
Tarar recalled the generous support and assistance given by
Canada to Pakistan during its formative years.
</P>
<P>
Leblanc said that Pakistan and Canada had a long history of
cordial relations, and Canada established diplomatic relations
with Pakistan within two weeks of its independence.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had an actively-evolving relations in the
field of trade and investment and shared views on issues of
international importance, Leblanc added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also actively collaborated with each other at
the United Nations and in U.N. peacekeeping operations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Leblanc stressed the importance of cultural exchanges which he
termed as an investment for the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
