<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Welcomes S. Africa's Tariff Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Chamber of
Commerce Friday welcomed the recent decision by South Africa that
60 percent of industrial and agricultural products from members
of the Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) enjoy no
import tariffs.
</P>
<P>
"The goodwill gesture by the South African government to scrap
import tariffs on 60 percent of industrial and agricultural
products as of January 1, 1999 is a positive contribution towards
achieving regional economic growth," said Danny Meyer, president
of the Chamber of Commerce, quoted by the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, this action serves to kick-start the process of
phasing out import tariffs on all products originating from
within the region faster than the eight years proposed in the
SADC trade protocol yet to be ratified by most member states," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
For the Zimbabwean business community, Meyer said, the
decision opened the door wider as access into the largest and
most lucrative market in the region would become easier.
</P>
<P>
But, he added, it was difficult to say which specific sectors
were likely to benefit in the absence of exact details of the 60
percent of industrial and agricultural products being proposed.
</P>
<P>
However, the move would in general have a major and positive
impact on the agricultural and industrial sectors as South Africa
was Zimbabwe's largest export market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swazi Cabinet Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A Swazi cabinet reshuffle
was announced Friday in Mbabane, South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Sishayi Nxumalo was appointed chairman
of the new Swaziland Investment Promotion Authority (SIPA), which
is expected to be launched by King Mswati III next week, the
prime minister's office announced.
</P>
<P>
Nxumalo's removal as deputy prime minister was not being
veiwed as a demotion, but rather as a recognition of his business
and political acumen which would stand him in good stead at the
vital investment promotion body, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Nxumalo was replaced by Foreign Minister Arther Khoza while
Economic Planning Minister Albert Shabangu replaced Khoza as
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Enterprise and Employment Minister Absalom Dlamini took over
Shabangu's portfolio whereas Natural Resources and Energy
Minister Majahenkaba Dlamini moved to enterprise and employment,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
