<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photographic Exhibition of Chinese Cultural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A four-week photographic
exhibition of "masterpieces of Chinese cultural relics" opened
Friday in Harare.
</P>
<P>
About 100 people including high-ranking officials from the
Zimbabwean government and foreign diplomats in Harare attended
the opening ceremony of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, S.J. Chifunyise, acting Zimbabwe's
Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of Education, Sport and
Culture, said the exhibition marks yet another milestone in the
very cordial relations existing between Zimbabwe and China.
</P>
<P>
"The exhibition will show the people of Zimbabwe for the first
time fifty beautiful pictures of Chinese cultural relics dated
from the neolithic age to the Qing Dynasty," he said, adding "It
marks a new development in cultural exchanges between our two
countries."
</P>
<P>
Also on the occasion, Qiu Bohua, charge d'affaires of the
Chinese Embassy to Zimbabwe, noted that up to December 1997, a
total of 19 cultural sites in China have been listed as world
heritage sites by the World Heritage Commission of the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
The exhibition was jointly organised by the Chinese Embassy
and the National Museums and Monuments of Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
