<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Dollar Gains in Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Dollar, which fell
sharply against major currencies at the end of last year, has
appreciated by about 12 percent since the beginning of the year
as stability slowly claws back onto the foreign exchange market,
Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa said Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, import pressure on foreign exchange reserves
was declining due to policy measures undertaken by the government
and reserve bank.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government ordered all corporate foreign
currency account holders to offload their foreign exchange onto
the market and increased the rediscount rate twice in less than
two months to 31.5 percent in a bid to prop up the tumbling
Zimbabwean Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Dollar, which fell 40 percent aga0HT+.h}wder immense import pr
essure, has been stable for the
past month trading at between 16 and 17 Dollars against the U.S.
Dollar.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the finance minister said, efforts by the
government to secure a three-billion-Zimbabwean-Dollar (about 180
million U.S. Dollars) one year stand-by balance of payment
facility with the International Monetary Fund and foreign
currency inflows from tobacco sales would further stabilize the
currency, the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The economic program we have put in place seeks to bring
about macro-economic stability and restore investor confidence,"
he said, adding "The process of fiscal consolidation will
continue in this context." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
