<HEADLINE> Special Rapporteur of Human Rights to Visit Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A special rapporteur of the United
Nations Commission on Human Rights will begin on Sunday an
official visit to the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Jiri Dienstbier, appointed on March 13, is making the trip at
the special request of the human rights commission.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Dienstbier will meet with Yugoslavia's
Minister of Foreign Affairs Zibadin Jovanovic and other government
officials on Monday in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
He will then travel to Pristina, where he will meet on Tuesday
with government officials, as well as representatives of the
Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
On his return, Dienstbier will make a preliminary report on his
findings to the commission, which is now meeting in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the special rapporteur follows the arrival in
Kosovo last week of a special team from the Office of the High
Commissioner for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The team was given authorization to visit Yugoslavia following
a request of the High Commissioner Mary Robinson in a letter to
President Slobodan Milosevic on March 11.  
</P>
</TEXT>
