<HEADLINE> Mugabe Sets Conditions for Stepping Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said Friday he is willing to step down provided this is by
popular demand through the right channels, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic
Front (ZANU-PF) rally at Gutu-Mupandawana growth point in
Masvingo Province, south Zimbabwe, Mugabe said he would only step
down through a resolution by his party's congress if a majority
of his followers felt it was time for him to go.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, while addressing a meeting of traditional chiefs and
local politicians at a local hotel in Gutu, Mugabe accused people
who had constantly stated that he had overstayed in power.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe has ruled Zimbabwe since its independence from British
colonialists in 1980.
</P>
<P>
"Some people say Mugabe has overstayed. These people say I
should take the example of South African President Nelson
Mandela. They do not look at the fact that the Mandelas have
their own way of doing things, and we have our own way of doing
things," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have our own constitution of how a president steps down,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
After listening to the various sentiments suggesting
factionalism had reached unprecedented heights in Masvingo, the
president tasked new Provincial Chairman Zephania Matchaba-Hove
with uniting the people.
</P>
<P>
"We, as the leadership in general, will do as much as we can
to help you achieve unity in the province," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
