<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brittan Praises China for Its Response to Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- European Commission Vice President
Leon Brittan Friday praised China for its "steady response" to the
Asian financial crisis, notably by resisting any devaluation of
its currency.
</P>
<P>
Brittan, in his closing speech at the third Asia-Europe
Business Forum, said: "It is my firm belief that China is coming
of age on the international scene."
</P>
<P>
Brittan stressed: "No country in Asia -- perhaps no country in the
world -- is more important for the future of the global economy
than China."
</P>
<P>
"Within the next twenty years, China is forecast to be the
second largest trading nation. Achieving her successful
integration into the world economic system is a huge strategic
challenge for Europe." he added.
</P>
<P>
To further develop EU-China relations in the coming years,
Brittan disclosed that the Commission has just set out a new
strategy, which he very much hoped will soon be endorsed by EU
member states.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his confidence in the ability of Asian countries to
bounce back from their current difficulties, Brittan said: "The
fundamentals of the Asian economies are sound; their peoples are
industrious, hard-working and well trained ... Asia can take off
again."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the measures the EU is going to take to ease the
Asian crisis, Brittan said it plans to set up an Asia-Europe
Meeting (ASEM) Trust Fund at the World Bank to help financial
restructuring and to prepare projects dealing with the social
aspects of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the Commission proposes to establish a network of
European financial experts to facilitate the provision of European
expertise in areas such as banking supervision and financial
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
And finally, in the event that it should become necessary, the
EU stands ready to provide substantial quantities of emergency
food aid, Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
"We very much hope, of course, that such a situation will not
come about," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
