<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-03 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq's Stance on Banned Weapons Justified: Aziz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said on Friday that the
inspections of the eight Iraqi presidential sites by a special
group of the United Nations have justified its position that it
has no prohibited weapons, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The outcome of the group's visit (to the presidential sites)
has verified Iraq's credibility and exposed (the falsehood of) the
allegations of the United States, Britain ... about those sites,"
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz in a statement carried by
the news agency.
</P>
<P>
The special group, formed under an agreement signed between the
U.N. and Iraq in February, comprises senior diplomats appointed by
the U.N. and weapons experts of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM). It completed the first round of its eight-day mission on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Through reviewing the huge fuss of the U.S. and Britain, "we
would notice the great difference between those lies and the
truth," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have alleged that Iraq has hidden its
weapons of mass destruction in the presidential sites, which they
have maintained should be inspected by the UNSCOM. But Iraq has
declared the sites off-limits for reasons of national sovereignty
and security.
</P>
<P>
The issue was at the core of a crisis last February when the
U.S., backed by Britain and some other countries, threatened to
take military actions to force Iraqi compliance with the arms
inspections.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan succeeded through a tough
mediation in persuading Iraq to open the presidential sites to
inspections, which helped defuse the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats of the special group have come to realize the
flatness of the lies of the U.S. and Britain, Aziz said, stressing
that what has been achieved is a triumph for the truth over the
falsehood.
</P>
<P>
He accused the two countries of using the lies as pretexts for
committing an aggression against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Such a result makes it imperative for the U.N. Security
Council to seriously work for lifting the eight-year-old unjust
embargo on Iraq ...," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed economic sanctions on Iraq, barring export of
oil, its main revenue earner, in 1990 after its invasion of
Kuwait. The U.N. Security Council will not lift the sanctions
until the UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has destroyed all its banned
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
