<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Hit by Salmonella </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 275 Canadians across the
country, most of them children, have been hit by salmonella
poisoning, a report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
There were cases of salmonella poisoning in every Canadian
province except British Columbia, according to the Globe and Mail
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"It's a substantial outbreak," Andrea Ellis, an epidemiologist
with the federal Laboratory Centre of Disease Control, was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Canada's most populous province of Ontario had only 529 cases
of salmonella poisoning in all of 1995. "So to have just under 200
cases in one month is quite significant," she said.
</P>
<P>
Salmonella bacteria are the most common cause of food
poisoning. The symptoms of salmonella poisoning include fever,
diarrhea, vomitting and abdominal cramps.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak was first noted last month in St. John's, New
Brunswick. Part of the cases could be linked to a packaged
luncheon snack.
</P>
<P>
The products have since been voluntarily recalled by the food
processor J.M. Schneider Inc..  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Central Banker Still Worries about Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- German central bank president Hans
Tietmeyer on Friday restated his doubt about the ability of Italy
and Belgium to considerably reduce their massive debts anytime
soon in order to live up to the stability criteria for the single
European currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a hearing at the German parliament, Tietmeyer
insisted that Italy and Belgium make binding commitments to reduce
their debt levels which are more than double the 60 percent of
gross domestic product that the EU Maastricht Treaty set as a
target for countries adopting the euro.
</P>
<P>
However, the German central banker was also careful enough to
duck any clear recommendation to disqualify the two countries from
the euro club. "The selection of participants remains a political
decision," he said.
</P>
<P>
The German cabinet last month already decided to follow a EU
Commission's recommendation to launch the euro in January 1999
with 11 member states, also including Italy and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The German parliament is due to vote on the issue on April
23-24. Given the support of all major political parties in Bonn,
the parliamentary approval is viewed as virtually certain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0035 </DOCNO>
