<HEADLINE> UNITA Stops its Radio Vorgan Broadcasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the United Nations Observer
Mission in Angola (MONUA) confirmed that Radio Vorgan had indeed
gone off the air.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior UNITA delegation has arrived in Luanda, the
capital of Angola, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
UNITA has been blamed for its failing to comply with its
commitments under the Lusaka Protocol, such as the
demobilization of all its troops, the shut down of the Radio
Vorgan and moving its leaders and offices to Luanda.  
</P>
</TEXT>
