<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-03 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Issue Billion Dollars of Eurobonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 3 (Xinhua) -- In the Middle East's largest single
borrowing, Lebanon signed an agreement with a French bank Friday
to issue 1 billion U.S. dollars Eurobonds.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Lebanese Minister of State for
Financial Affairs Fuad Sinyoura and Nigolas Kostantiku,
representative of the Paribas bank which helped Lebanon issue 5
billion U.S. dollars Eurobonds a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The issue is aimed at bringing down the country's ballooning
deficit and reduce large domestic debt.
</P>
<P>
The National News Agency quoted Sinioura as saying that the
issue is the largest single borrowing ever in the Middle East, and
also for the world's emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be divided into a five-year offering carrying
8.5 percent interest rate and 8 percent for three-year, both in
the same amount.
</P>
<P>
"We decided to further issue 1 billion dollars in light of the
strong demand for the earlier issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Lebanese, Arab and western investors were rushing
to buy into the country's 5 billion dollars Eurobonds marketed
also by Paribas bank through the "roadshows," a series of
presentations that move from one country to country.
</P>
<P>
The issue, the minister said, will serve to reduce the
government's heavy burdens imposed by the public debt which has
reached 15 billion dollars in January. Out of it, 12.6 billion
dollars are internal.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to reduce large domestic debt with the high
interest rate through borrowing lower interest-rate debt in
foreign currencies," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the outside borrowing will also pave the way for the
Lebanese private sector to gain enough loans to invest in the
country's economy, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
