<HEADLINE> Russian-Japanese Informal Summit Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto Friday in a telephone
conversation agreed to postpone their second informal meeting
scheduled on April 11-12 until April 18-19, the Interfax news
agency quoted Yeltsin's press service as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders agreed that they should meet after the Russian
parliament confirms ministerial nominations for the new Russian
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin dismissed his government entirely on March 23 for it
did not cope with a number of key social problems and nominated
35-year-old Sergei Kiriyenko as new prime minister. The State Duma
is facing debate over the premier's appointment.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Hashimoto said both sides are ready to achieve
serious results to follow up their first informal meeting in
Krasnoyarsk, Russia, last November, when they reached a
"Yeltsin-Hashimoto plan".
</P>
<P>
The second "no-necktie" meeting between the Russian and
Japanese leaders will be held in Kawana, Japan.  
</P>
