<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese PM Calls for Promoting Asia-Europe Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji called
on Asian and European countries to increase mutual investment and
reduce trade barriers so as to further push forward their
bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the statement in his address to the second Asia-Europe
Meeting here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, entitled "Enhance Mutually Beneficial
Cooperation and Promote Common Development," Zhu urged Asia and
Europe to give top priority to economic cooperation and trade.
</P>
<P>
To this end, Zhu suggested that the two sides give play to
their respective advantages and open up various cooperation
channels.
</P>
<P>
Zhu appealed to the two continents for further enhancing their
cooperation in the scientific and technological field.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries, he said, should relax the restrictions on
technical transfer and provide developing countries with advanced
technologies, which he believed serves the interests of developed
countries themselves.
</P>
<P>
Zhu suggested an "Asia-Europe Scientific and Technological
Ministerial Meeting" be held for ASEM members to work for specific
measures for developing the scientific cooperation. China stands
ready to host the proposed meeting, the Chinese premier said.
</P>
<P>
On working for closer international cooperation in the
financial sector, Zhu hoped the two sides will strengthen mutual
co-ordination and support, conduct closer cooperation between
their financial supervisory and regulatory departments.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis shows that to take precautions
against financial risks is the shared responsibility and in the
common interests of both sides, Zhu pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides should actively participate in
international financial support programs to guard against and
resist financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also called on the two sides to step up political dialogue
and consultation.
</P>
<P>
"We should cherish and develop the existing sound atmosphere
for and momentum of dialogue, replace confrontation with dialogue
and conflict with cooperation, and strive to find and expand the
converging points of common interests," Zhu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
