<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Records Decrease in Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, with Africa's biggest
popluation, has recorded a decrease in its population growth rate
from 3.2 percent in the 1980s to 2.8 percent in 1995, official
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Nkess Nkposong, an official from the Federal Ministry of
Health told a workshop in Ibadan City Thursday that the total
number of children a Nigerian woman would give birth to by the
end of her reproductive life was 5.5 in 1995, compared to 6.6 in
1981-82.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's population was estimated at 104 million as in 1997,
the 10th largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Projecting from the 1991 census, Nigeria would have a
population of 180 million by the year 2017, said Nkp osong, who
is an assistant director of the Department of Community
Development and Population Activities.
</P>
<P>
"Information from 1995 surveys indicates that Nigeria may have
entered the first stage of demographic transition," the official
said, "This is a situation where there is rapid decline in the
birth and death rates with the former declining more rapidly so
that population growth is declining."
</P>
<P>
The official, however, regreted that Nigeria's infant
mortality rate is still very high with 114 per 1,000 while the
maternal mortality is extremely high with an estimated number of
1,000 per 100,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
The situation may have to do with the fact that about 13
percent of Nigerian girls began to bear children at age 15 and
nearly half by 20.
</P>
<P>
Poor medical service is also to blame, Nkposong said, adding
that there is currently one hospital bed to approximately 900
Nigerians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
