<HEADLINE> Liberia Bans Unauthorized Arms Holders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles Taylor
announced Friday afternoon that any authorized security men found
carrying weapons in the capital Monrovia will be arrested and
jailed.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said this will affect the police, soldiers of the armed
forces of Liberia and even his own bodyguards the Special
Security Service.
</P>
<P>
According to a British Broadcasting Corporation report
monitored here, the president has told his bodyguards to limit
their activity to the confines of the Executive Mansion, the seat
of the government.
</P>
<P>
As for the soldiers, they should leave their rifles in the
military barracks before going for duty.
</P>
<P>
However, the permanent members of the security forces and
positions of security places would have to be armed, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
He said the move is taken to prevent the possibilities of
troubles spreading from neighboring Sierra Leone, adding that "If
we are attacked, we can't use sticks and bottles to defend the
country."
</P>
<P>
"We are a sovereign country. We have to bring arms in and
we'll not hide them. Nobody will stop us," Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) accused
Taylor's government of smuggling weapons into the country in
defiance of the United Nations' arms embargo.
</P>
<P>
"If Liberia is to continue to be part of it (ECOMOG), the
force needs to be responsible and topless structured," Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
"We support ECOMOG, but only an ECOMOG which respects the
president of an ECOWAS (Economic Community of West African
States) country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
