<HEADLINE> Kurdish Rebels Accused of Smuggling Drug in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Friday accused the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) of being actively involved
in the rampant drug trafficking in the country, the Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Most cases of drug trafficking in Turkey have been found
relating to the PKK, a Turkish security official declining to be
named was quoted by the news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
"There are indications that money from the drug smuggling has
become one of the important financial sources (of the PKK)," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has used the money to support its 14-year-old fighting
against the Turkish government in an attempt to set up an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said the PKK hired the unemployed or illegal
immigrants in Turkey to serve as street sellers or smuggle drug to
Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Some PKK branches in some European countries are also involved
in these unlawful activities," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is one of the key routes to transfer drugs from Asia to
Europe. According to official statistics, around 10 tonnes of
hashish and 3.5 tonnes of heroin were seized in Turkey last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
