<HEADLINE> Botswana Ex-Army Chief Nominated Vice-President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Botswana
Democratic Party (BDP) has nominated just-retired army commander
lieutenant-general Seretse Khama as vice-president of Botswana,
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted the president's
office as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
Khama's appointment will be subject to his election into
parliament within four months and the attainment of parliamentary
approval.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the BDP's parliamentary majority ensures a
smooth passage of the nomination through the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Khama would contest a by-election at Serowe North, the family
birthplace and seat of the Bamangwato paramount chief.
</P>
<P>
He is the eldest son of Botswana's first president, late
Seretse Khama who was also founder of the BDP. He followed
his father as paramount chief of the Bamangwato, the country's
largest and most influential tribe.
</P>
<P>
The presidential office said the date of the by-election would
be announced as soon as incumbent member of parliament Roy
Blackbeard, former agriculture minister, retires from active
politics.
</P>
<P>
Khama, who retired from the army on March 31 along with
President Ketumile Masire, has already been appointed as Minister
of Presidential Affairs and Public Administration, which is
considered to be the president's right hand.
</P>
<P>
The ministry controls the army, police, information and
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
It is widely accepted that the new president, Festus Mogae,
brought Khama into his government to help reunite the BDP, which
has seen various factions fighting for control of the party.
</P>
<P>
Mogae succeeded Masire after Masire's retirement Tuesday.
Endiem

