<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Venture Capital Investment on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Venture capital investments in
Canada rose 66 percent in 1997, making another year of
record-setting growth.
</P>
<P>
Venture capital financings totaled 1.8 billion dollars (1.26
billion U.S. dollars) last year, after increasing by 64 percent to
1.1 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new money was invested in 794 companies, a 51 percent
increase from 525 the year before, said reports Friday.
</P>
<P>
Venture capital refers to investment in small companies and
other situation such as turnarounds, where there is a
higher-than-normal degree of risk.
</P>
<P>
Last year, technology companies were the largest recipients of
venture capital. Of all the firms that received financing last
year, 500 were technology-based, which received a total of 1.2
billion dollars or 66 percent of the investment.
</P>
<P>
Within the technology sector, computer-related businesses were
the biggest recipients of capital, with 191 companies attracting
466 million dollars. That was a sharp increase from 222 million
dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Other major users of venture capital include the biotechnology
sector -- 79 companies received 203 million dollars -- and the
communications industry, with 59 firms that took in 140 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEM Leaders Issue Statement on Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The leaders voiced strong support to the full implementation of
the International Monetary Fund's (IMF) reform programs and
stressed that policies should be implemented in an "open,
transparent, and non-discriminatory manner."
</P>
<P>
They called for a strengthened capacity of the IMF to respond
to financial difficulties "in a timely and decisive manner," an
enhanced and more transparent global IMF surveillance system, and
strengthened cooperation, regulation and supervision in financial
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also recognized the importance of devising
strategies to secure private sector involvement in providing
financial assistance and maintaining continued access to trade
finance for economic recovery within the framework set by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Asian and European leaders welcomed the
creation of an ASEM trust fund at the World Bank to help finance
effective technical assistance and advice both on restructuring
the financial sector and on finding effective ways to redress
poverty.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed the need of reforming domestic financial
systems and economic structures, and of considering the social
impact of the financial difficulties in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The statement made it clear that with continued implementation
of sound economic and financial policies, "the overall impact of
the Asian financial crisis upon the world economy was likely to be
material but manageable."
</P>
<P>
The leaders also pledged that all the issues mentioned above
should be followed up vigorously by ASEM finance ministers to
consider concrete measures of implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
