<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Businesses Like Toll-Free Numbers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- High demand by Canadian businesses
for toll-free numbers has forced phone companies here to introduce
877 numbers starting Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian businesses use 800 and 888 numbers for customers who
wish to place orders or get product help. At present, Canada has
about 250,000 toll-free numbers in service.
</P>
<P>
The 888 numbers, launched just two years ago, ran out three
years earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of 877 numbers across North America will add
another 7.89 million combinations firms can use, said reports
Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the current rate, Canadian phone companies are expected to
run out of 877 numbers by September 1999. After that, it will
introduce 866 and 855 toll-free prefixes.
</P>
<P>
It took almost 30 years for phone companies in North America to
run out of 800 numbers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Commission Offers New Humanitarian Aid Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
cleared a major new package of humanitarian aid worth 86 million
ecu (1 ecu=$1.07) for the former Yugoslavia, a release from the
the UN spokesman's office said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The European Community Humanitarian Office (ECHO) will manage
the package, which will enable humanitarian organizations,
including UN agencies, the International Committee of the Red
Cross and other non-governmental organizations, to carry out
coordinated programs through the end of February 1999.
</P>
<P>
In Bosnia and Herzegovina and in Croatia, the aid will mainly
support the return of displaced persons and refugees, in close
coordination with the Office of the High Representative and the UN
High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
This new humanitarian aid infusion brings ECHO's total
contribution to the former Yugoslavia since the beginning of the
conflict to 1.5 billion ecu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
