<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London, Frankfurt Stocks End at New Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe had a
record breaking week, with London and Frankfurt both hitting new
record closing highs Friday and Paris ending slightly lower after
all of the three markets touched all-time intraday highs.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares had soared 50 points
earlier to reach an intraday record of 6,105.3, inspired by Wall
Street's big gains Thursday, before ending marginally up, yet
hitting its third consecutive record closing high.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that earlier Wall Street inspired gains gave way
to a tenacious two-way pull, but the index managed to stay above
the 6,050 level, closing at 6,064.2, up 11.4 points or 0.19
percent on the day, and a rise of 124.9 points from last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking on the last trading day of the tax year helped to
wipe out early gains, and some caution was noted ahead of next
week's Bank of England monetary meeting.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt staged an even sharper rally, with
the DAX-30 index finishing the week at a fresh closing peak of
5,223.52, up 46.86 points or 0.91 percent after having hit a new
intraday record of 5,246.04.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that the market maintained a positive tone despite
declines in Asia, boosted by a firmer Dow, a strong dollar and
sharp gains in some heavyweight stocks.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris closed slightly lower on record
volume, down from a fresh intraday high of 3,987.82 on concerns
that Wall Street would be hit by a weaker than expected March U.S.
jobs report.
</P>
<P>
The index closed at 3932.02, down 3.86 points or 0.10 percent,
but a rise of 121.79 from last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
