<HEADLINE> Clinton Says He Will Do His Best Despite Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Friday he does not intend to be deterred from doing his work
as the nation's chief executive by Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's investigation of sexual misconduct allegations.
</P>
<P>
Back home after his African trip, Clinton appeared in the Rose
Garden today to express his concern over the Senate-passed budget
blueprint that rejects his domestic priorities.
</P>
<P>
Following a formal statement, he was asked about reports on CNN
and in U.S. News and World Report that Starr is being urged by
some of his deputies to indict former intern Monica Lewinsky and
to name Clinton as an unindicted co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
The weekly magazine said the debate in Starr's camp took on a
new impetus after a federal judge's dismissal of the Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit against the president.
</P>
<P>
In response Clinton said, "I'm not going to comment on that.
I'm going to try to do what the Supreme Court said I should do and
not be deterred in any way by that. I'm going to do my best."
</P>
<P>
The reports, attributed to "informed sources" but not
identified said some members of Starr's team are convinced only an
indictment of Lewinsky can bring the question of obstruction of
justice and suborning perjury to a public trial now that the Jones
case has been thrown out.
</P>
<P>
U.S. News said a faction in Starr's office believes the special
counsel should continue his federal grand jury investigation and
pile up evidence to be turned over to Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
