<HEADLINE> Leblanc Calls for Stronger Economic Ties with Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Canadian Governor
General Romeo Leblanc called here Saturday for stronger business
relations with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon hosted by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
in his honor, Leblanc said, "under the Colombo Plan of the
nineteen-fifties, and later under bilateral arrangements, some two
billion (U.S.) dollars from our country has helped to develop your
own."
</P>
<P>
This partnership has left its mark all over Pakistan, in
projects ranging from small schools and clinics to the mighty dams
at Warsak and Tarbela, said Leblanc.
</P>
<P>
"We still continue our cooperative work in infrastructure, but
we balance it by a growing emphasis on human development" he
added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Canada and Pakistan are now working together on
environmental protection, the regulation of energy, financial
credit systems, human rights, health care, education, and
training, especially for women, and on strengthening social and
economic institutions generally.
</P>
<P>
The governor general said that Pakistan has been "a leader in
economic reforms." It has created a friendly environment for
investment and growth. And Canada's partnership with Pakistan is
broadening from aid to a growing trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
Canada wants to give renewed impetus to bilateral economic
relations, said Leblanc, adding that "Our friendly and productive
relationship has the potential for impressive growth."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif said on the occasion that his government
has initiated wide-ranging economic reforms. "It is our objective
to create and nurture a corporate culture in Pakistan, wherein the
private sector could play its role in nation building," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the attractive investment incentives included in the
new and business friendly investment policy made Pakistan a land
of many opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed his confidence that the current two-way trade
and the level of Canadian investment in Pakistan can be increased
manifold.  
</P>
</TEXT>
