<HEADLINE> Uganda: ADF Rebels Eat Captives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the Allied Democratic
Forces (ADF)in Uganda have eaten captives, the daily New Vision
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lieutenant Colonel Francis Okello, the
commanding officer of the 53rd Battalion of Uganda Army, as
saying that the ADF rebels have eaten an unspecified number of
abducted people and even one of their commanders who was unable
to move due to his illness.
</P>
<P>
But Okello did not give the name of the commander.
</P>
<P>
In a broadcast of Radio Tooro, Wycliff Mwesigwa, the
intelligence officer of the Second Division of Ugandan Army,
confirmed the cannibalism in Okello's briefing to the local
media.
</P>
<P>
Broadcasting from Radio Tooro covers the west of Uganda,
Rwanda and parts of Tanzania and the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
There are at least 50 local people still held by ADF rebels.
The captives are used by the rebels as laborers and human shields
in fightings.
</P>
<P>
ADF is a Uganda rebel group with hundreds of its remnants
active in western Uganda and eastern Congo. It had some 1,500
fighters in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Ugandan Army and the government troops of Congo
have launched a joint operation against ADF rebels in their
common border areas. The coordinated operations have forced the
rebels to retreat northward to Kivu Province of the Democratic
Congo, Okello said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
