<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgians, Dutch Tie in Davis Cup Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Filip Dewulf on Saturday gave the
hosts some hope of advancing to the quarter-finals of the world
group Davis Cup tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian ace did not drop a set en route to pulling the host
side back on equal footing with the visiting Dutch side with one
win each from the two opening singles.
</P>
<P>
Dewulf, ranked 54th on the ATP tour, overwhelmed Sjeng
Schalken, 60th, 7-5, 6-2, 7-5 in a little over two hours in their
opening singles match that was put off from Friday due to rain.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's match was also delayed by rain and play was
interfered by gusts of wind that affected the serves on both sides
of the court.
</P>
<P>
Yet a more determined Dewulf threw in all he got to make
Belgium one up on the scoreboard. The Belgian player turned out
more in control via placement shots that kept Schalken busy
returning shots from difficult angles in the second set.
</P>
<P>
Dewulf then came from 2-4 down in the third but almost
squandered three match points in his final serving game. He at
last pulled off the winner after grabbing an advantage ensuing the
deuce that he allowed too hastily.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Dewulf will pair off with Libor Pimek in the doubles
that is put off from Saturday, before meeting in the first of the
reverse singles Jan Siemerink who entertained hundreds of Dutch
followers on Friday by winning the first opening singles.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Dutch, ranked 29th on the ATP tour, routed
71st-ranked Johan van Herck 6-4, 6-3, 4-6, 6-1 in three hours.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands and Belgium met four times previously in the
Davis Cup, each winning two encounters. The Dutch whitewashed the
Belgians in their last Davis Cup tie in 1994. 
</P>
