<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Ministry Urges Prudent Use of Iodized Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Health issued
an order today banning the forced sales of specified iodized
products and foodstuffs, and urged consumers to exhibit prudence
when using related products.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Health explicitly prohibits public health
departments, medical institutions and individuals from using
administrative economic means to compulsorily market iodized
products and foodstuffs to kindergartens, nor can they claim that
related products help eliminate diseases caused by iodine
deficiencies," according to a ministry official.
</P>
<P>
The official's remarks came in response to an outbreak of
health-threatening reactions suffered by people taking iodized
calcium nutrients sold in several counties in Shandong and Anhui
Provinces in east China and northeastern Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The official urged consumers to protect their health by seeking
medical advice prior to their use of iodized nutrients.
</P>
<P>
China has drafted a plan to eliminate diseases associated with
iodine deficiences the year 2000, with the main measure for
attaining the goal centered on promoting the use of iodized salt.
</P>
<P>
However, the official reiterated that administrative and
economic means cannot be used to sell over-the-counter iodized
calcium nutrients and specified iodized foodstuffs to
kindergartens and schools, nor can related products be promoted in
any other manner. Instead, he said, products must be sold through
normal market channels.
</P>
<P>
"Units and individuals are strictly prohibited from marketing
related products in the sole pursuit of profit," according to
official.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Ministry of Health issued an urgent notice
calling for public health departments nationwide to launch a
comprehensive examination of iodized foodstuffs and related
products sold as nutrients.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
