<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Exports to Rwanda Increase by 120 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's exports to Rwanda
increased by 120 percent from 19.1 million U.S. Dollars in 1995
to 42 million U.S. dollars in 1996, the Monitor reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a report published in the daily newspaper Friday, the
Market Research Department of Uganda Export Promotion Council
said that the import share of Rwanda from Uganda increased from
34.7 percent in 1995 to 69 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The figures did not include smuggling and micro-level business
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The staple commodities Uganda exports to Rwanda are foodstuffs
including beans, maize, soya beans and fish. Manufactured
products such as plastics, bicycles, petroleum products,
beverages and mattresses are also high on the list of the Ugandan
export goods.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's exports to Rwanda and the eastern parts of the
Democratic Republic of Congo are on the increase in the wake of
the improving political and economic conditions in the two
countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report has been designed to help business communities to
study the market situation in the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
