<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Motorola (China) Electronics
Company in Tianjin, northern China's largest port city, plans to
export products valued at 1.54 billion US dollars in 1998, up 53
percent on 1997.
</P>
<P>
The company, established by US-based Motorola in 1992, reported
1997 sales of 19.4 billion yuan, with exports for the year
standing at 980 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Motorola (China) was listed as one of Tianjin's top 50
exporters in 1997, and ranked as one of China's leading
foreign-funded enterprises in terms of exports.
</P>
<P>
The company exports include engineering plastics, liquid
crystal displays, mini-motors, transformers and computer
components.
</P>
<P>
Motorola has invested over 1.2 billion US dollars in China
since 1987, including investments of one billion US dollars in
Tianjin alone. The parent company plans to increase the amount to
2.5 billion US dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Motorola currently leads US companies in terms of investments
in China.  
