<HEADLINE> U.N. Diplomats Leave Baghdad After Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Twenty senior diplomats of the
United Nations' special group responsible for accompanying arms
inspectors to eight Iraqi presidential sites left here Saturday
afternoon after an eight-day, first round of inspections.
</P>
<P>
Janayatha Dhanapala, head of the special group, told reporters
before departure that he was happy about the outcome of his
mission, and he would submit a final report on the results of the
mission to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 20 senior diplomats of different countries had accompanied
arms experts from the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction in searching Iraqi
presidential sites since March 26.
</P>
<P>
The mission was completed Thursday night. According to
diplomatic sources, they found no prohibited weapons in those
sites.
</P>
<P>
The eight presidential sites were at the center of an arms
inspection crisis between Iraq and the U.N. which was defused
after Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz signed an
agreement on February 23.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, Iraq agreed to open its eight presidential
palaces to inspections in which arms experts should be accompanied
by a multinational group of 20 diplomats whenever they visit the
presidential complexes.
</P>
<P>
The United States, backed by Britain and some other countries,
had threatened to launch air strikes to force Iraqi compliance
with U.N. arms inspections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
