<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Families Essential for Social Security in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Families remain as an essential
basis for social security in China, and their functions for
nurturing the young and caring for the elderly, disabled and
infirmed cannot be entirely replaced by the social welfare,
according to Chinese sociologists.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the '98 Beijing International Conference on
Family, Social Security and Social Welfare which opened today in
the Chinese capital, Lu Xueyi, director of the Institute of
Sociology at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, noted that it
would be extremely difficult for the State to replace the care and
support provided by families, However, he did note the existence
of complementary functions between families and society in terms
of social security.
</P>
<P>
Lu explained that penetration of the welfare state into
families requires significant increase in funding, and
acknowledged that only advanced economies can afford such a high
costs.
</P>
<P>
"State and societal penetration in family functions such as
care and support have primly met the physical needs of people,"
said Lu, adding that "care and support nurtures frequent
interaction between family members and is irreplaceable in terms
of communications and emotional well-being."
</P>
<P>
The prestigious sociologist also noted that the existence
attachments and morality ensure that family support and care are
voluntary actions free of the need for external intervention, and
therefore guarantee efficiency and require no additional external
management costs.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have, in fact, been deliberating welfare
policies and introduced programs to downsize their welfare systems
since the end of the 1970's. The State-family relationship has
indeed been on the cutting edge of change. State responsibilities
for families are gradually being shifted to the families
themselves in order to relieve heavy financial pressures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Families Essential for Social Security in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts participating in the conference also pointed out that
current social phenomena, such as changing value concepts, aging
populations and the rising divorce rate, as well as both
unemployment and layoffs have challenged traditional Chinese
family functions centering on care and support.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yiyun, a research fellow with the Institute of Sociology
at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, noted that most
families continue to provide security for family members,
particularly in terms of providing emotional support and ensuring
the material well-being of children.
</P>
<P>
Most families continue to care for and protecting their
dependent members, as well as the elderly, disabled and infirmed,
said Chen. She also pointied out that this has been the major
factor prompting the Chinese government and various NGOs to attach
great importance to building civilized families, or families with
improved social ethical and cultural progress. Moreover, she
added, related activities have been one of the primary tasks of
social development in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that healthy and stable families are prerequisites
for social stability.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is sponsored by the Institute of
Sociology at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, the Chinese
Association of Family Culture Studies and the Jinglun Family
Center.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 scholars and experts from 13 countries and
regions are expected to discuss methods for improving the social
security system in the course of modernization, industrialization
and urbanization, as well as the potential of families to offer
resources and assume responsibility for improving social
security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Antarctic Expedition Returns to Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese ship Xuelong (Snow
Dragon) docked at Shanghai Port today marking the successful
conclusion of a scientific expedition to the South Pole.
</P>
<P>
The Xuelong departed Shanghai Port on November 15, 1997, to
begin the 14th expedition to the Antarctic continent since the
first expedition was mounted in 1984. The Xuelong sailed 22,883
nautical miles over a period of 142 days.
</P>
<P>
The vessel transported fuel, equipment and food to two Chinese
research bases on the South Pole -- the Changcheng (Great Wall)
Station and the Zhongshan Station -- and conducted scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
Members of the expedition also concentrated on environmental
protection activities which included collecting waste and rubbish
which had accumulated since establishment of the Changcheng Station
and returning same to Shanghai for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Significant progress has been recorded in terms of the research
plan listed in China's 1996-2000 Guidelines for Antarctic
Research. The team's studies of the ice coverage in the Antarctic
will not only provide a deeper understanding of the laws of global
climate changes, but will also greatly enhance predictions for
future changes.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia are planning to build an airport in the
ice-covered region, with experts currently in the process of
selecting one of four runway constructions plans. The airport is
scheduled for completion in the year 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shake-up of S. African Intelligence Structures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- A major shake-up of South
African Military Intelligence (MI) and an examination of its role
and that of police intelligence are predicted after an MI report
was proved flawed, Saturday Star reported.
</P>
<P>
The MI report, which was handed directly to President Nelson
Mandela by South African National Defense Force (SANDF) chief
general Georg Meiring on February 5, claimed that senior African
National Congress (ANC) officials were plotting a coup against
the government.
</P>
<P>
Named in the report were Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, president
of the ANC Women's League and ex-wife of Mandela; former ANC
official and now co-leader of the United Democratic Movement
Bantu Holomisa, Meiring's heir-apparent; SANDF Chief of Staff
Siphiwe Nyanda and Robert McBride, a Foreign Ministry official
who was detained last month in Mozambique for alleged arms
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The judicial commission of inquiry appointed by Mandela last
week found that the process of compiling the report was so flawed
that it was impossible to take its allegations seriously.
</P>
<P>
Doubts have now been cast on the military intelligence's
credibility and its future is in question, said Saturday Star.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is continuing consultations with key cabinet ministers
on the next course of action and the findings of the commission.
</P>
<P>
He will brief leaders of the opposition parties early next
week on the findings of the commission.
</P>
<P>
Military intelligence had breached the laws governing
intelligence operations in South Africa, the paper quoted sources
within the security establishment as saying.
</P>
<P>
The National Strategic Intelligence Act of 1994 prohibits MI
from covertly collecting domestic military intelligence or
foreign non-military intelligence -- something which was done to
compile the report.
</P>
<P>
The controversial report has also cast doubt on the
circumstances around the arrest of McBride.
</P>
<P>
The report did not follow accepted procedure. It should have
gone through the National Intelligence Coordinating Committee
(NICOC) and the Ministry of Defense before it reached the
president.
</P>
<P>
Meiring explained in a statement earlier this week that he
breached the procedure because the information was sensitive and
could not be treated in the normal way.
</P>
<P>
But he failed to explain why NICOC knew nothing about the
decision to gather information on McBride. The surveillance had
been conducted from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Until about two months ago, MI head Dirk Verbeek sat on NICOC
as chief of intelligence of the SANDF, and before Meiring
received the information, Verbeek, as head of MI, would have
received it. This was confirmed by Meiring's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Meiring's statement also failed to explain how the report was
leaked to media shortly after McBride's arrest in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
He failed to explain why SANDF generals were said to be
planning to meet with Suiker Britz, the man responsible for
investigation of illegal weapons possession in the South African
Police Service's Special Investigation Unit.
</P>
<P>
Britz, who did not meet McBride in Mozambique during his
information-gathering trip to that country, said later that there
was enough evidence to convict McBride of arms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Britz confirmed that he was approached by an SANDF general who
wanted urgently to meet him to discuss the McBride case. The
SANDF said it was working with the police.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was suspicious of the report from the outset because
it implicated trusted members of his government in an alleged
coup based on information from one single source -- Vusi Madida,
also known as Vusi Mbatha, a self-confessed informer for the
former security forces.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was forced to go public with his concerns and appoint
a judicial commission of inquiry last Friday when the report was
leaked to the press and used to fuel rumors that McBride was
guilty of gun-running.
</P>
<P>
Madida, the sole source of information in the MI report, has
also been arrested along with McBride. Madida was reported last
week as having told Mozambican police that he and McBride planned
to send arms to Fretilin guerrillas fighting for East Timor's
independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Intelligence sources said that both Madida and Alex Mamba, who
Madida named in his statement to the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission as a weapons smuggler with whom he had contact, worked
for police intelligence and MI. Mamba is believed to have tipped
off the Mozambican and South African police that McBride had
walked into the trap set for him last month.
</P>
<P>
The South African government said it believed that with the
1999 general election drawing near, it was possible that elements
dissatisfied with the current government would try to launch a
disinformation campaign to destabilize the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
