<HEADLINE> Cameroun Denies Nigeria's Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The government of Cameroun has
denied Nigeria's allegation of attacking Nigerians in the
disputed Bakassi peninsula, over those ownership the two
countries have been clashing since early 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to the Post Express Friday, Cameroun has informed
international public opinion that there was no military
confrantation in the 1,000-sq km peninsula last month as
announced by the Nigerian side.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Defense Headquarters indicated that in an attack on
March 19 Cameroun's helicopters armed with machine guns wounded
more than 40 Nigerians, most of whom market women and school
children.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun said non of its aircraft over-flew that area on that
date and consequently vehemently and categorically denied the
Nigerian allegations.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have filed the case of ownership over Bakassi,
believed to be rich in fishery and oil resources, to the
International Court of Justice in the Hague, the Netherlands,
which is in the course of hearing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
