<HEADLINE> Beijingers Join Effort to Plant Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Communist Party and State leaders
and some two million Beijing residents and members of the People's
Liberation Army participated in today's annual tree-planting
activities held throughout the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Related activities attracted people from all walks of life,
including officials, members of the PLA and armed police,
government employees, workers, farmers and students.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, the Beijing Municipal People's Congress designated the
first Sunday of April each year as a voluntary day for planting
trees, with related efforts over 14 years helping to increase
general public awareness of the importance of afforestation,
ecology and the environment.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the forest rate coverage for the
Chinese capital reached 38.26 percent by the end of 1997, with
landscaped areas covering 33.4 percent of the total urban
area. Both rates represent considerably increases in figures for
only a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
As part of an ongoing landscaping and beautification program,
the municipal government has pledged to raise the city's forest
cover rate coverage to 40 percent by the end of this year, a level
which will be achieved one year ahead of the official
schedule. Reaching the objective will require that Beijing
residents plant an average of 3-5 trees each during the year.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary statistics indicated that a total of 1.5 million
trees were planted during today's activities, with participants
also cleaning landscaped areas covering some four million square
meters.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more than 200 Chinese and foreign students
attending the Beijing Language and Culture University (BLCU)
gathered in the institution's new International Garden to plant a
tree representing peace and friendship.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 students from 162 countries and regions have
attended the BLCU, the country's leading center for training
teachers of the Chinese as a Foreign Language.
</P>
<P>
The BLCU, founded in 1962, was known the Beijing Language
Institute until 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
