<HEADLINE> HK Plays Active Role in Protecting Intellectual Property Rights: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, a leading world
financial and trading center, has been playing an active role in
the protection of intellectual property rights, a local government
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Customs and Excise Training School, Secretary
for Trade and Industry of the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) Chau Tak-hay underlined the need to
"maintain Hong Kong's integrity as an international financial and
trading center."
</P>
<P>
He said the Customs and Excise Department of the Hong Kong SAR
government has been doing well in "suppressing piracy activities
at all levels, from import to manufacture and from storage to
distribution."
</P>
<P>
The department has been highly regarded both locally and
internationally by law enforcement agencies as well as trademark
and copyright owners in the fight against copyright infringement
and counterfeiting, Chau said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from protecting intellectual property rights, he added,
the department has been doing very well in protecting revenue from
dutiable goods, in dealing with illegal traffic of narcotics and
other contraband, in safeguarding the credibility of Hong Kong's
export licensing and origin certification systems and in enforcing
copyright and trade descriptions legislation.
</P>
<P>
The secretary expressed the hope that the department upholds
this fine reputation and continues to play an important role in
the protection of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
He also told the probationary inspectors and probationary
customs officers at the school the need for them to know more
about every aspects of "our country," noting that local residents
had been living in a society and cultural environment very
different from that of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"For everyone of us there is a need to know more about every
aspects of our country -- her culture, history, geography and even
 the way of life and thinking of our mainland compatriots," Chau
said, adding: "All of us need to increase our sense of national
identity so that we may be better equipped to implement faithfully
the policy of 'One Country, Two Systems'."  
</P>
</TEXT>
