<HEADLINE> Forest Fires-Affected Philippine Provinces Declared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos Saturday
placed under a state of calamity all provinces, cities and towns
with at least 25 hectares affected by forest fires due to the El
Nino weather disturbance.
</P>
<P>
"All provinces and cities/towns suffering from forest fires
covering an area of 25 hectares or more are hereby declared
calamity areas," Ramos said in a memorandum to Defense Secretary
Fortunato Abat.
</P>
<P>
Ramos ordered all affected local government units to utilize
local government funds and personnel, equipment as well as
volunteers to put out such fires.
</P>
<P>
He chided local officials for their failure to initiate
effective preventive measures to control the spread of forest
fires which have reportedly destroyed at least 2,000 hectares of
forest during the recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Ramos earlier released a total of 10 million pesos from the
Calamity Fund to contain the forest fires in Palawan province, an
island in the southern Philippines, and in other areas in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Aside from Palawan, forest fires have also affected more than
4,000 hectares of virgin forest in the provinces of Benguet,
Antique, Negros Occidental and Davao.
</P>
<P>
The central Benguet province was the worst hit, with 2,000
hectares of trees destroyed.
</P>
<P>
In Palawan, a fireman was killed Thursday after a burning tree
fell on him as he fought fires.
</P>
<P>
The government has asked its Southeast Asian neighbors, the
United States and Canada for help in putting out the raging forest
fires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
