improve the environmental quality of the capital," Li said,
adding that "motor vehicles' emissions are particularly harmful and
should be dealt with carefully."
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), exhibited his adroitness at
planting trees and commented that "planting trees will beautify
our environment and benefit our descendants."
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the end of 1997 show the Chinese capital's
forest coverage rate reached eight percent, with the landscaping
rate for the city proper standing at 33.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
