<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Closes Down Seven Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
announced here Saturday that seven troubled banks will be closed
as a step in the banking reform.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Finance Minister Fuad Bawazir said
another seven banks will be under the close supervision of the
Indonesian Banking Reform Agency (IBRA), a government-sponsored
agency established in January to restructure the country's
troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on the public not to worry about their
funds because the government's guarantee remains.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that Indonesia closed down commercial
banks in the country since October last year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the government liquidated 16
ailing commercial banks in a bid to improve efficiency of the
country's banking system. 
</P>
