<HEADLINE> Cambodian Government Urges Prince to Cut Ties with Khmer Rouge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian government reaffirmed
its stance Friday that Prince Norodom Ranariddh must stop his
military cooperation with outlawed Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum released by government also asked Ranariddh to
order his troop to stop fighting against the government forces
before he can be allowed to take part in the election.
</P>
<P>
"Price Ranariddh indeed maintained an unholy alliance with the
Khmer Rouge that was indeed brought into the cities to be used as
the backbones of the military coup in July 1997 to eliminate his
rival ahead of the general election scheduled for 1998," said the
memorandum.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "Failure of Prince Ranariddh to publicly
disassociate himself from the Khmer Rouge will not liberate him
from being a political hostage of the Khmer Rouge."
</P>
<P>
"He must also prove that his order to ceasefire has been
carried out by his troops. If not, he must disassociate himself
from them and declare them outlawed. Failing to do that will deny
him and his party the rights to run in the election according to
political party law," said the memorandum.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum also said that "the royal pardon was granted
only to Prince Ranariddh" and could not be used
for his convicted generals because it is not part of the Japanese
peace plan.
</P>
<P>
Before departing for Bangkok on Friday, Ranariddh expressed his
hope that his generals should also be pardoned.
</P>
<P>
"I never abandon anybody and I think my generals are
reasonable, I hope that royal pardon will be granted to them under
the Japanese peace mediation and under U.N. facilitation to those
two generals," Ranariddh said.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh ended his first five-day home trip to Cambodia on
Friday under full protection provided by the government, the
United Nations organization and other foreign institutions.
</P>
<P>
He was pardoned by his father King Norodom Sihanouk on March 21
after he was sentenced to 35 years in prison on March 4 and 18 by the
Cambodian Military Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
