<HEADLINE> 2 Sentenced to Death in Iranian Killing Case in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- An anti-terrorist court in
Pakistan Saturday awarded death sentence to two man for the last
year killing of five Iranian cadets in Rawalpindi, sister city of
the federal capital.
</P>
<P>
The court, however, acquitted a co-accused of the murder
charges and reserved its judgment on the fate of three absconders.
</P>
<P>
Those who were awarded death sentence included Muhammad Asif
and Muhammad Yaqub, while Qari Muhammad Siddique was acquitted.
All the accused were present when the judgment was announced.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian cadets along with their Pakistani driver were
gunned down in Rawalpindi, about 20 km south of the capital, on
September 17 last year. The Pakistani law enforcement agencies
arrested six men and charged them with murder.
</P>
<P>
The local administration made strict security arrangements
around the jail on the occasion. No one, including journalists,
were allowed to enter the jail.
</P>
<P>
In order to curb the rising sectarian violence in the country,
the Pakistani government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
introduced an anti-terrorism law shortly after it came to power
early last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
