<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South African major real
estate companies have substantially increased their service to
locals intent on relocating or investing in property overseas,
newspaper Saturday Star reported.
</P>
<P>
Seeff Residential Properties, one of the leading real estate
companies in South Africa, was quoted as saying that it had
entered into a joint venture with Ray White Real Estate of
Australia to market Australian residential and commercial
properties in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Australia has always been a popular relocation destination for
the South Africans, Andrew Smith, managing director of Seeff
Residential Properties said.
</P>
<P>
"Uprooting and re-establishing a family in a new country is
never easy. Seeff's aim with the new joint venture is to take the
bumps out of this well-traveled road," he said.
</P>
<P>
Smith believed that the recent easing of foreign exchange
controls has globalized the South African property market and it
is now essential for top property firms to diversify
internationally.
</P>
<P>
The recent Property Expo at Midrand, a city between
Johannesburg and Pretoria, reflected this growing interest in the
overseas market.
</P>
<P>
At the exhibition, the Sovereign Surfers Paradise Hotel on
Australia's Gold Coast canvassed South African investment in two
new hotel apartment suite developments, and the stand attracted a
lot of attention.
</P>
<P>
According to local real estate companies, South Africans also
seem extremely keen to buy property in London. Pam Golding
International reported that it had been inundated with requests
from hundreds of serious buyers for a foothold in the British
property market.
</P>
<P>
