<HEADLINE> Portuguese Parliament Chief Visits Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April (Xinhua) -- President of Assembly of the
Republic of Portugal Almeida Santos arrived in Maputo Friday,
starting his week-long official visit to the southern African
nation.
</P>
<P>
The daily Noticias reported Saturday that the visit of the
Portuguese parliament chief at the invitation of President of
Assembly of the Republic of Mozambique Eduardo Mulembwe was aimed
at strengthening the relations between the two parliaments.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, Santos had been living in Mozambique
from 1953 to 1974. He returned in May 1974 to Portugal to act as
the minister of international coordination in the provisionary
government, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
On April 7 and April 9, Santos will hold two talks with his
Mozambican counterpart. And he will pay a visit to the Cahora
Bassa Dam in northwestern Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Santos will also meet Mozambican President
Joaquim Chissano and Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi.
</P>
<P>
Santos has come to Maputo soon after Portuguese State
Secretary of Foreign Affairs and Cooperation Luis Amado finished
his five-day visit to Mozambique. 
