<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another 1,000 Iraqi POWs Back from Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Another batch of about 1,000 Iraqi
prisoners of war (POWs) released by Iran have returned to their
homeland, the Iraqi News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agency said Iraq again set free 50 Iranians captured during
their eight-year war from 1980-88 in the latest POW exchange, a
decade after the fightings ended.
</P>
<P>
A swap ceremony, the second in three days, was held Friday
evening at the border city of al-Mundhariya under the supervision
of the Red Cross Society. The first batch of 800 Iraqi POWs
released by Iran arrived home Thursday evening; and on the same
day Iraq freed 62 Iranian POWs.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Iraqi Foreign Under-Secretary Riyadh al-Qaisi
as saying that more POWs will be released in the coming days under
a scheduled program agreed on by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's al-Zawra weekly on Thursday reported that Iran will set
free 6,000 Iraqi POWs in the biggest such release since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said Iran still holds up to 20,000 Iraqis as POWs after
39,000 were released in 1990, an accusation Iran often denied.
Iran says Iraq keeps 6,000 to 10,000 Iranian prisoners, though
Iraq declared that it does not have any.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here believe the repatriation of POWs will
help remove the obstacles that have been preventing the two
neighbors from resuming diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
During their bloody war in the 1980s, an estimated 1 million
Iranian and Iraqis were killed or wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
