<HEADLINE> Kyrgyz Government Downsized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev has
decreed to cut the government positions by ten to improve
efficiency of the government work, the Interfax news agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a dispatch from Bishkek, capital of Kyrgyzstan, the Russian
news agency said that the positions of deputy prime ministers
in charge of agriculture, finance and social programs have been
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
The president also abolished the Ministry for Cooperation with
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) Members and shifted its
functions to the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Only one deputy prime minister position has been retained in
the reshuffle and Kyrgyzstan's representative to the four-nation
Integration Committee and the Customs Union will be given the rank
of a deputy premier, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Akayev is to sign a decree appointing Bishkek Mayor Boris
Silayev as deputy prime minister as well as new ministers, 35 to
40 percent of them will come from the present cabinet, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
On March 25, the president appointed Kubanychbek Zhumaliyev as
the new prime minister. And the appointment gained overwhelming
support from the parliament. 
</P>
