<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Study Use of Nuclear Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- To meet the growing demand for
energy, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) has
decided to explore the use of nuclear power, the Philippine News
Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear experts in the region will meet within the next three
months to study how the grouping can work together to ensure
nuclear safety and manage nuclear waste in Southeast Asia, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The decision, made by the ASEAN Committee on Science and
Technology (COST) during a meeting ending here Friday, came in
response to the projected energy demands of continued development
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The committee also decided that a fresh approach was called for
if cooperation among members in the field of science and
technology was to be boosted.
</P>
<P>
The committee considered commercializing some of its more
successful projects, such as the ASEAN Science and Technology
Information Network which consists of data bases of interest to
researchers, development planners, policy makers and
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
This move is part of the concerted effort that ASEAN has been
making to involve the private sector in its schemes and programs.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN says its science and technology programs are aimed at
beefing up the region's industrial competitiveness. 
</P>
