<HEADLINE> Male Kindergarten Teachers Play Important Role (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Wearing earphones and seated in
stark darkness, a group of urban kids listen attentively to the
sounds of nature -- deafening thunder and the howl of wild
animals. Their teacher believes this will help improve the
children's courage.
</P>
<P>
Pan Haohan, employed 10 years ago as the city's first male
kindergarten teacher, aims to transform the timid kids into
persistent and dauntless citizens adaptable to an increasingly
competitive society.
</P>
<P>
The 40 male kindergarten teachers in Shanghai are particularly
conspicuous among the city's 20,000 female kindergarten teachers
for their different thoughts toward pre-school education.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey covering 204 administrators and teachers of
kindergarteners and 284 parents shows that 76 percent of them
believe that male teachers will be popular among the children and
62 percent of them agree that male teachers would be more
effective in improving the students' creativity and personalities.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai-based Wenhui Daily has recently begun a write-in
column encouraging readers to comment on whether the hiring of
male teachers indicates that children need masculine guidance in
kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
Feng Yuwei, director of the Shanghai Teachers Training Center,
said that the participation of male teachers in kindergarten is
necessary, but the success of pre-school education does not depend
solely on the gender of the teacher. The psychological quality,
teaching methods and educational objectives also are important, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that China's adoption of the one-child
policy in the late 1970s has unexpectedly created an unfavorable
circumstance for the healthy growth of children because of the
lack of sibling competition in the one-child families.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a large number of Chinese teachers, especially
female teachers, have habitually treated bold and aggressive kids
as "bad kids" and regard obedient kids as model ones, which has
also had a negative impact on the competitive nature of
children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
