<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Population Heads for Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan experts predict that
Kenya's population growth rate is set to sharply decline and its
population is expected to be stabilized as the country moves
toward the final stage of the population transition period.
</P>
<P>
Murugaru Kimani, Lecturer at the Nairobi University's
Institute of Population, said that the theory of demographic
transition has three stages, according to a Daily Nation report
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the early stage of a country's development is
characterized by high rates of both birth and death and most of
African countries is at the stage.
</P>
<P>
During the middle stage, the death rate declines but birth
rate remains high, said the lecturer, adding that Kenya has moved
from the early stage and now is in the middle stage.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the final stage of the transition has low death
and birth rates and Kenya is heading for the final stage.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Kenya started experiencing a fertility decline in
the late 1980s, he pointed out that fertility rates fell from 3.8
percent in 1979 to 3.3 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Although Kenya's population is expected to rise from the
present 28.8 million to 36 million by 2025, experts believe that
the population will eventually reach stabilization stage where
the number of births will roughly harmonize with the number of
deaths.
</P>
<P>
Some experts argue that the decline in population growth rate
can be speeded up through the introduction of contraceptives and
sex education in schools.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, some 33 percent of married women use all manners of
contraceptives and the figure is set to rise, according to the
1997 World Population Data Sheet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
