<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SLankan Tea Output Goes Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The total production of Sri
Lanka's black tea in February this year reached 20.3 million kg, a
22 percent increase over the corresponding month of 1997, Tea
Board sources said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The black tea production in January/February this year stood at
43.49 million kg as against 37.97 million kg produced in the same
period of 1997, showing an increase of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
High grown tea output in February this year was 6.114 million
kg, compared with 5.661 million kg a year earlier, while medium
grown tea production went up from 3.256 million kg to 4.858
million kg. Low grown tea output was 9.325 million kg, compared
with 7.770 million kg.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's tea production was 276.8 million kg last year, a 7
percent increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tea is one of Sri Lanka's main export items and the source of
over 25 percent of its export earnings. It is also the world's
largest black tea exporter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
