<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Pair Takes Ice Dancing World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian pair Anjelika Krylova
and Oleg Ovsyannikov clinched the ice dancing title at the World
Figure Skating Championships in Minnesota on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian pair, showing their unbeaten streak from very
beginning, dominated the rest of field in all four sessions,
including compulsory dance, second compulsoy dance, original dance
and free dance.
</P>
<P>
The pair won three silvers at 1996 and 1997 World Figure
Skating Championships and the 1998 Nagano Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"It was a bit hard to skate today because it was the end of a
long and tiring season," said Ovsyannikov after the competition.
"We had many competitions, however, I am very happy about how we
skated here and how the audience appreciated our perfomance."
</P>
<P>
Marina Anissina and Gwendal Perizerat of France took the second
place and the bronze medal went to Canada's Shae-Lynn Bourne and
Victor Kraatz.
</P>
<P>
The two pairs, also competed in the first rank throughout the
four programs, presented sweet dances to the American
skating-lovers.
</P>
<P>
The French pair, 1998 Olympics bronze medalists, were satisfied
with their presentation.
</P>
<P>
"This is by far the best program we have skated," said Peizerat
after the competition. "Our technique was perfect. With each step
you could feel love between Romeo and Juliet."
</P>
<P>
Anissina, who began skating together with Peiserat in 1993,
said, "I am so proud that the crowd reacted so well to the
program."
</P>
<P>
The Canadians, who finished third in the last two World
Championships and placed fourth at the 1998 Olympics, also
expressed their happiness with their result.
</P>
<P>
"That's the best we have ever skated the free dance. That's a
great way to end the season, skating in Minneapolis in front of
such a great crowd," Bourne said.
</P>
<P>
The crowd, including a quite big number of Canadians, responded
warmly to the ice-dancers.
</P>
<P>
"I think right after the Olympics we got all the frustration
out of us," added Kraatz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
