<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Puts Off Vote on Premier Minister Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma (the lower
house of parliament) Friday postponed a vote on President Boris
Yeltsin's prime minister nomination after receiving a letter from
him.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Yeltsin withdrew his March 27 demand for a Duma
vote on the nomination, but asked again for its approval of the
prime ministership for 35-year-old Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
The move, a legal formality allowing the Duma one more week to
consider the candidacy, was taken "for the sake of preserving
political stability and public accord," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin initially threatened to dismiss the Duma unless it
approved the nomination. But his conduct was strongly opposed by
his legislative opponents, who were enraged by his nominating
Kiriyenko without consulting them.
</P>
<P>
To avert a looming showdown, Yeltsin held a meeting with
legislative leaders on Thursday, and agreed to hold a broad
discussion with them on the formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said Chairman of the State Duma
Gennady Seleznev had announced the Duma would study the nomination
in the following week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
