<HEADLINE> UNITA Pledges Soon to Complete Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 4 (Xinhua) --wXYpZrent of the National Union
for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) Jonas Savimbi pledged
Friday in Bailundo to complete the peace process as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
In his Bailundo headquarters, Savimbi told the visiting U.S.
presidential envoy Paul Hare that UNITA will soon finish the
remaining tasks stipulated in the Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
Returning to Luanda, Hare disclosed UNITA's plan to the press
at the airport. He said that Savimbi expressed his hope that all
problems hindering the peace process could be resolved as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Hare added that the UNITA leader assured him that in all areas
controlled by UNITA except Bailundo and Andulo, the
reestablishm_@orities will begin on April 6.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was satisfied with the recent developments in
the Angolan peace process, particularly, with some UNITA leaders
moving to the capital city and its radio shut down.
</P>
<P>
However, Hare said that there are still some hurdles on the
way to full peace. He called on the Angolan government and UNITA
to carry out the demilitarization of remaining rebel fighters and
the reestablishment of state authorities in all areas controlled
by the opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
The United States is one of the observers monitoring the
Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Luanda Donald Steinberg who accompanied
Hare also congratulated on the big step forward toward peace in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the relocation of UNITA headquarters to Luanda,
Government spokesman in the Joint Committee for Peace Process
Higino Carneiro said Friday that what his government cared about
is the relocation of UNITA leadership to the capital city while
Savimbi can live where he likes to, but he should abide by the
law.
</P>
<P>
As for the bloodsheds resulting in violation of the Lusaka
Peace Accord by the remaining rebel soldiers, Carneiro said that
since UNITA had declared demilitarization, the intervention of
the Angolan armed forces and the national police was legitimate.
</P>
<P>
The government was just fighting against the outlaws, he
added. 
</P>
