<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Former President's House Declared Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's former president Kenneth
Kaunda's house has been declared a prison with immediate effect,
government-controlled Zambia Daily Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This move is in accordance with a statutory instrument signed
by home affairs minister Peter Machungwa in the government
gazette published on April 1, said the Daily.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Machungwa, who confirmed the declaration of Kaunda's
Kalundu house in Lusaka as a prison, as saying Friday that Kaunda
who is under house arrest is no longer a detainee but a remandee
that needed to be kept in prison.
</P>
<P>
"Under the laws of Zambia, all persons charged with criminal
offences are supposed to be kept in prison and to that effect we
have declared Kalundu house, where Dr. Kaunda is restricted, as a
prison," said the home minister.
</P>
<P>
The statutory instrument empowers the commissioner of prisons
to be in control of the Kalundu house and also vests powers in
the officer-in-charge to allow visitors twice a week or in
special circumstances allow further visits at his discretion.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, also opposition leader, was detained last December for
alleged involvement in Zambia's foiled military coup last
October. Later under the pressure from international community,
he was shifted from prison to his Kalundu house under house
arrest.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was formally charged with concealment of treason one
month ago but the trial is supposed to be a marathonic one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Yen's Dive Prompts Panic in Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Asian currencies, including the
Thai baht, and the region's stock markets took a dive during the
week amid warnings that Japan's economy is on the brink of
disaster.
</P>
<P>
The bearish scenario was compounded by U.S. rating agency
Moody's investors service's announcement on Thursday that it had
lowered Japan's country ceiling and currency ratings to negative
from stable, driving the yen to 135.20 to the dollar, its worst
level since August 1991.
</P>
<P>
The announcement also sent Japan's key stock market Nikkei
Average down a further 185.12 points to end at 15,517.78 after the
previous day's plunge of 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moody's said it changed its outlook for Japan's economy because
of the inability of Japanese leaders to hammer out policies to get
the world's second-largest economy out of a seven-year economic
downturn and the country's worsening fiscal situation.
</P>
<P>
Norio Ohga, chairman of Japanese electronic giant Sony, added
to the fuel, predicting at a briefing earlier that the Japanese
economy is on the brink of collapse and at risk of a long spiral
of deflation.
</P>
<P>
Ohga's comments followed a jolt from a central bank survey
released hours earlier showing confidence among Japanese companies
plunged in late March.
</P>
<P>
Amid worries that a tumbling yen and a sinking Japanese economy
would worsen the regional economic turmoil, most regional
currencies, which had been tracking the embattled yen the whole
week, dipped further and breached psychological levels.
</P>
<P>
The Thai baht fell to 41.30 against the dollar from Thursday's
Asian trading close of 40.99 -- reversing the gains of the past
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian ringgit dropped to 3.7900 from 3.7400, the
Singapore dollar weakened to 1.6330 from 1.6275, and the
Indonesian rupiah to 8,550 to 8,500.
</P>
<P>
Most stock markets in the region also plummeted on concern over
economic reform in Japan and a weakening in regional currencies.
Thai share prices dived 2.4 percent in thin trade on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong share prices fell 1.2 percent lower in pre-holiday
trading Thursday, while Singapore's stock prices ended 1.1 percent
lower.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Malaysia's key stock index closed 2.6 percent
lower, and share prices plunged 4.2 percent on the Korea Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
"Basically Japan is being exposed as something of a disaster
area as opposed to the engine of economic growth it once was," a
Siam Sanwa Securities analyst in Bangkok said.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that something bad is happening in Japan, so
there is going to be a serious spillover effect here, particularly
with the exposure of Japanese banks in Thailand and the region.
This could lead to a real crisis," said a Seamico Securities
analyst in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The only positive news on Thursday was that Indonesian shares
rose 3.3 percent amid news reports that the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the Indonesian government will be able to reach an
agreement by next week on the country's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
IMF officials, however, said that some work still needed to be
done on Indonesia's 74-billion-dollar private debt.
</P>
<P>
Despite the chaos caused by the gloomy prospects of the
Japanese economy, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, who
was in London for the second Asia-Europe summit, promised to take
action.
</P>
<P>
"Japan will take the necessary economic measures and, at the
same time, provide assistance to the countries of Asia as well,"
he reportedly said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
