<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, April 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian State Duma (the lower house of
parliament) Friday postponed a vote on President Boris Yeltsin's
prime minister nomination after receiving a letter from him.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Yeltsin withdrew his March 27 demand for a Duma
vote on the nomination, but asked again for its approval of the
prime ministership for 35-year-old Sergei Kiriyenko.
(Yeltsin-Duma-Nominee)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 34 people, including 26 children and five
women, were killed and 16 others seriously injured Friday in a
road accident in India's central State of Madhya.
</P>
<P>
The Pioneer newspaper reported Saturday that the tragedy
occurred when a mini-bus fell into a 30-feet-deep ditch due to
brake failure near Delawadi Ghat, 60 kilometers from Bhopal,
capital of Madhya. (India-Road Accident)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma Friday accused the
Group of Seven industrialized countries of breaking an agreement
to replace the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said the agreement in 1994 had two new nuclear plants to
replace Chernobyl, scene of the world's worst nuclear accident in
1986. (Ukraine-Canada)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev announced a reshuffle
of the government on Friday, cutting the number of cabinet posts,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Akayev signed a decree retaining the two posts of Prime
Minister and Deputy Prime Minister, abolishing the previous
structure of a First Deputy Prime Minister and three Deputy Prime
Ministers. (Kyrkyzstan-Reshuffle) 
</P>
