<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange closed the week on a lower note due to concern over
corporate failures and impending problems in the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
At the close of this week's trading, the 100-quality stocks
Composite Index plunged 61.14 points to 666.48 from last week's
close, the all-share Emas Index fell 14.44 points to 169.65, the
Industrial Index was 88.12 points lower at 1,217.99 while the
Second Board Index lost 15.29 points to 166.42.
</P>
<P>
The CI touched its highest intraday level of 728.29 early
Monday morning before closing the week at its lowest level.
</P>
<P>
The market succumbed to selling pressure except for slight
bargain-hunting on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of construction and engineering-based Wembley
Industries being placed under receivership by PhileoAllied Bank
following its failure to repay loans raised concern of other
corporate failures should banks turn aggressive in demanding
repayments, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the widely-anticipated merger announcement of
finance companies with the deadline on March 31 was discounted by
the market while poor corporate results failed to lift sentiment,
the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Finance counters were also suppressed towards the week's end by
reports that 30 percent of the 100,000 finance companies staff
might be laid-off following the mergers while banks having
exceeded their exposure limit to a single client did not help
matters.
</P>
<P>
Uncomfortable about conditions in the market, foreign funds
started selling bluechips with Thursday seeing programmed selling
from U.S. and U.K. funds.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the main board volume fell to 799.821 million
shares worth 1.995 billion ringgit (530.585 million U.S. dollars)
from last week's 857.898 million shares valued at 2.152 billion
ringgit (572.34 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover decreased to 90.645 million shares
worth 200.180 million ringgit (53.239 million U.S. dollars) from
91.094 million shares valued at 246.792 million ringgit (65.636
million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
However, off-market volume this week expanded to 76.455 million
shares worth 237.795 million ringgit (63.243 million U.S. dollars)
from 53.994 million shares valued at 202.994 million ringgit
(53.987 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 companies requested for temporary suspension of
their shares pending results, mergers and other announcements this
week when there were no new listings.
</P>
<P>
The suspended counters were Advance Synergy, Bernas, UMG Group
and Kim Hin on Monday followed by Malpac, Ekran, Wembley, Bescorp,
Len Cheong, Arab-Malaysian Finance, Affin Holdings and ACF
Holdings on Tuesday, Esprit, Maybank and SEA Devt on Wednesday,
Kurnia Setia on Thursday and Apex Equity on Friday.
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 41.952
million shares traded, industrial products 64.466 million,
construction 78.036 million, trading/service 197.490 million,
infrastructure 4.390 million, finance 173.228 million, hotels
3.273 million, properties 78.726 million, plantation 28.924
million, mining 6.547 million, trusts 369,000, closed/fund 542,000
and loans 18.570 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
