<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of the
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
higher.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market, April south ended the week at
2,275 ringgit (605.05 U.S. dollars) per ton, 55 ringgit (14.62
U.S. dollars) better than last week's close of 2,220 ringgit
(590.42 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals market is expected to be in a tight-range
trading next week with prices to move within the current levels on
the back of the currency factor, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), tin price closed the
week 88 sen (23 U.S. cents) higher at 20.73 ringgit (5.51 U.S.
dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
This week saw the price heading upwards gradually since Tuesday
on the back of a continued lower ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The price ranged between 19.85 ringgit (5.28 U.S. dollars) and
20.73 ringgit (5.51 U.S. dollars) per kg this week.
</P>
<P>
Turnover for the week settled at 321 tons against last week's
turnover of 184 tons.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM may trend lower next week as a downward technical
correction may take center stage and erase some of its previous
hefty gains, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
During the week, rubber prices on the Malaysian rubber market
were on their uptrend as many foreign enquiries came in, boosted
by the continued depreciation of ringgit.
</P>
<P>
April RSS One ended the week seven sen better at 276.50 sen
(73.5 U.S. cents) per kg from 269.50 sen (71.6 U.S. cents) per kg
last week while SMR 20 added 6.50 sen per kg at 273.00 sen (72.6
U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization daily market
indicator price for April 2 stood at 192.57 Malaysian/Singapore
cents versus 187.43 cents on March 26.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average was at 190.57 cents versus 188.32
cents.
</P>
<P>
The local rubber market is expected to rally further next week
if ringgit continues to depreciate against the U.S. dollar,
dealers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
