<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Sector Remains Stable in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The public sector of the economy
in east China's Shanghai municipality, a leading industrial and
financial center, remained stable in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The latest data from the municipal statistics bureau show that
the publically owned sector completed added value of 259 billion
yuan, accounting for 77 percent of the municipality's total GDP
(gross domestic product) in 1997, matching the previous year's
level.
</P>
<P>
The publically-owned sector is composed of state-owned and
collectively-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
State-owned firms completed 191 billion yuan of added value, or
57 percent of the total GDP. The state economy still plays the
major role in key sectors such as commercial, financial and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's non-public sector maintained rapid development,
according to the statistics. The municipality has 63,000 private
firms and 160,000 self-employed households, completing 76.9
billion yuan in 1997 and accounting for 23 percent of the total
GDP. The figure was 0.6 percent higher than in the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
