<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Explores New Markets for Manpower Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is increasing its
manpower export mainly to the Gulf states after having lost some
overseas employment markets in such Asian countries as Malaysia,
South Korea and Singapore hit by the monetary turmoil, press
reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The number of Bangladeshi migrant workers in Malaysia, one of
the biggest venues for Bangladesh's manpower, fell short of the
target by 23 percent in 1997, according to statistics of the
Bureau of Manpower, Employment and Training.
</P>
<P>
The target of manpower export to Malaysia was fixed at 300,000
in 1997, but the actual number was recorded at about 230,000, the
statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the number of Bangladeshi migrants to South Korea
came down to 2,844 in 1997 as against 66,631 in 1996, and
Bangladesh was able to send only 448 persons during the first two
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the on-going drive to seek new markets is
to maintain the manpower export at a reasonable level, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Manpower export is a major foreign exchange earner for
Bangladesh. In 1997, about 1.53 billion U.S. dollars in
remittances was sent back home as against 1.36 billion dollars in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
