<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Schedule Announced for International Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Skating Union
(ISU) will improve its events schedule in the next season and to
amend the rules for the free dance.
</P>
<P>
"We now have 20 official ISU events over a seven month season
and we have introduced prize money, a Grand Prix, and a Junior
Grand Prix," said ISU president Ottavio Cinquanta at a press
conference in Minnesota on Friday.
</P>
<P>
From next season, Cinquanta said, "we will have four
Championships -- Europeans, Four Continents, Worlds and Junior --
seven Grand Prix events and nine Junior events."
</P>
<P>
On ice dance judging, he said, the technical committee was
working to amend the rules to include some specific requrements
and elements for the Free Dance.
</P>
<P>
"This will help the skaters and judges know better what is
expected of them," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Cinquanta, the proposals will be discussed and
voted on at the ISU Congress in Stockholm in June. "It is the
member federation that will make this final decision," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
On the new proposal for two free programs, the president said
there is a new proposal to be discussed at Congress that would
require skaters to have two free programs in a season.
</P>
<P>
The requirement, he said, would be that a skater must present a
different program at the World Championships to the one they
present at the European or Four Continents Championships.
</P>
<P>
"I am in favor of this new proposal because it would make for
more varity for the audience," said Cinquanta.
</P>
<P>
He also said that more money must be invested to educate the
judges.
</P>
<P>
"Judges and coaches could have ongoing seminars where coaches
are giving information, and the judges are accepting the
information," Cinquanta said. "This education is necessary for the
future success of ice dancing."
</P>
<P>
On the age of skaters, the ISU president said that the age
should not be younger than 15 as a matter of health.
</P>
<P>
"We have to protect the young skaters and the minimum age is
now 15. This is a health protection consideration," he said. "The
only power ISU has over skaters is when they skate in an ISU
event."
</P>
<P>
Also he said, skaters have their own right to decide whether
they stay on not in the sport.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot persuade skaters to remain in the sport. And in the
end, it's their own decision," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
