<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan Leads Women's Short at World Figure Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese American Michelle Kwan,
a runner-up at the 1998 Olympics, led the Women's short program at
the World Figure Skating Championships at Minneapolis, Minnesota
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old skater, who is competing for her fifth world
championships, made steady triple jumps and performed artfully to
cheer the crowd of spectoters at Target Center and received almost
the full marks both in technichs and presentation.
</P>
<P>
Kwan is heavily favored to win the world championship this time
with Olympic gold medalist Tara Lipinski and bronze medalist Chen
Lu skipping the competition.
</P>
<P>
Poland's Anna Rechnio, who was placed 14th at 1995 World
Championships and 19th at 1998 Olympics, surprised the American
skating lovers when she remarkably finished second in the short
program.
</P>
<P>
France's Laetitia Hubert skated third. The 24-year-old French
woman also improved from her sixth position in the 1997 World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
However, two hopeful Russians skated flatly. Irina Slutskaya,
who was placed fifth at the Olympics and bronze medalist at 1996
World Championships, finished fourth today. Maria Butyrskaya, who
was fourth place finisher at the Olympics this year, skated fifth
at the short program.
</P>
<P>
The figure skating rule gives the short program 33.3 percent of
the overall score while the free program 66.7 percent. The free
program will be held Saturday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
