<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Win Doubles for 2-1 Lead in Davis Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Todd Woodbridge and Mark
Woodforde won the doubles in straight sets to pace Australia for a
2-1 lead in the Davis Cup tie against Zimbabwe in Mildura on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Woodies, who have won the last five Wimbledon doubles
titles, defeated Byron and Wayne Black 6-4, 7-6 (8-6) and 6-2,
putting Australia into a favorable advantage before the two
reversed singles to be played on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Black brothers, who also play singles for Zimbabwe, matched
the Woodies during the first two sets but were less effective on
the big points.
</P>
<P>
Australia took the first set after 33 minutes with just one
service break when Byron Black double-faulted on set point in the
10th game.
</P>
<P>
In the second set, the Zimbabweans kept all their games before
bowing out in the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
The third set was dominated by the Woodies who broke Byron's
serve in the third game then broke Wayne's in the fifth as they
cruised to victory.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's reverse singles, Australia's reigning U.S. Open
champion Pat Rafter is scheduled to play Wayne Black while Byron
Black is slated to meet Jason Stoltenberg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
