<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko Plans to Raise More Funds for Military Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government will work
out a plan to raise more funds for military reforms by scaling
down defense spending and selling redundant military assets,
acting Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported that Kiriyenko and acting
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev held a two-hour meeting to discuss
military reforms.
</P>
<P>
The two decided that the committee for military construction
would be retained, but a financial guarantee committee for
military reforms, chaired by former First Deputy Prime Minister
Anatoly Chubais, would be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko praised the progress already made in military
reforms, saying that despite limited financial allocation, defense
officials had worked out clear goals for reforms and worked hard
to achieve them.
</P>
<P>
He said the pace of military reforms must be maintained and the
set tasks must be accomplished in accordance with the actual
financial situation.
</P>
<P>
Due to financial difficulties, Russian servicemen has not been
paid for a month and the government has a large amount of defense
orders to pay, Kiriyenko said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
