<HEADLINE> Ukraine: G-7 Breaks Chernobyl Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
Friday accused the Group of Seven industrialized countries of
breaking an agreement to replace the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said the agreement in 1994 had two new nuclear plants
to replace Chernobyl, scene of the world's worst nuclear accident
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the Group of seven during talks with visiting
Canadian Natural Resources Minister Ralph Goodale who announced
that Canada was to give 20 million U.S. dollars to help build two
new nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
Goodale also promised assistance with advanced technology in
drying and saving nuclear materials during his visit.
</P>
<P>
The aid package included equipment for removing anti-personnel
mines with which Canada had much experience.
</P>
<P>
President Kuchma said Ukraine welcomed the assistance. The two
men also discussed other bilateral cooperation issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
