<HEADLINE> Kyrgyz Government Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev
announced a reshuffle of the government on Friday, cutting the
number of cabinet posts, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Akayev signed a decree retaining the two posts of Prime
Minister and Deputy Prime Minister, abolishing the previous
structure of a First Deputy Prime Minister and three Deputy Prime
Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Kubanychvek Zhumaliyev was kept on as Prime Minister, but
former First Deputy Prime Minister Amangeldy Muraliyev, who was in
charge of industry, was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
Forty percent of the new cabinet were first-time office holders.
</P>
<P>
The Kyrgyz parliament on March 25 approved the president's
nomination, which named Zhumaliyev as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Political and economic experts commented that the abolition of
the deputy prime ministers was to improve working efficiency and
cut down on middle men. 
</P>
