<HEADLINE> Martin Luther King's Memory Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Martin Luther King Jr.'s
"Mountaintop" speech rang out again Friday night at the church
where the late American civil rights leader delivered his last
public address 30 years ago -- the night before he was
assassinated.
</P>
<P>
"Martin believed in this country, that black and white can live
together," The Associated Press quoted Bishop Chandler Owens of
the Church of God in Christ as saying. "And I think we have come a
long way toward that goal. Every step we make in that direction,
we must remember the great dreamer."
</P>
<P>
The memorial service in Memphis, Tennessee was part of a
weekend long "Pilgrimage to Memphis," a series of seminars and
other events honoring King and other champions of the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
King was killed on April 4, 1968, by a rifle shot while
standing on the balcony of the Lorraine Motel, now a civil rights
museum. King was in Memphis to support a strike by sanitation
workers.
</P>
<P>
The opening session for the pilgrimage was held at Clayborn
Temple, the church were the marches for the sanitation strike
began and ended.
</P>
<P>
"We saw ourselves as the liberation movement, the freedom
movement, a justice movement, a movement that wanted to transform
America," said the Rev. James Lawson, a close King associate, said
at the opening session.
</P>
<P>
He said, while the civil rights movement of the 1950s and '60s
achieved many of its goals, much work remains to be done, and King
set the example of how to do it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
