<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Opposes Interference in Its Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavian Foreign Minister
Zivorad Jovanovic reiterated Friday that international pressure on
the Kosovo crisis amounted to outside interference in his
country's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Russia's First Deputy Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov, Jovanovic said that interference in the internal affairs
of other countries violated the United Nations Charter and
international laws, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
He said he was surprised that the six-nation Contact Group on
the former Yugoslavia interfered in the internal affairs of the
Republic of Serbia and Yugoslavia through the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov, who arrived Thursday for a working visit, briefed
Jovanovic on Russia's stand on the U.N. Security Council
resolution for an arms embargo against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic and Serbian
President Milan Milutinovic also met Russia's first deputy foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed an arms embargo Tuesday to
pressure Belgrade to open unconditional dialogue with ethnic
Albanian leaders in the troubled Serbian province Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has a 90 percent ethnic Albanian majority which has been
seeking independence from Yugoslavia since 1981. Violence there
has been growing this year after the failure to implement an
education agreement reached between Milosevic and the leader of
ethnic Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova. 
</P>
</TEXT>
