and the Communist Party of Vietnam (CPV) agreed here Friday to
further promote the friendly cooperation between the two parties
and the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during the talks between the Chinese
delegation, headed by Zeng Qinghong, secretary of the Secretariat
of the CPC Central Committee, and the Vietnamese delegation, led
by Phan Dien, chairman of the Department of Economy of the CPV
Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zeng arrived here Thursday for a six-day official goodwill
visit to Vietnam at the invitation of the CPV Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
The two sides briefed each other about the situations in their
respective countries and exchanged views on how to advance
friendly cooperation between the two parties and the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that the relations between the two parties had
continuously developed since the normalization of the
Sino-Vietnamese ties in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The China-Vietnamese relations were important in China's
foreign policies, especially in its policies towards neighboring
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng extended his heartfelt congratulations to the
accomplishment the CPV made in its 10-year reforms. He believed the
Vietnamese people, under the leadership of the CPV, were able to
materialize the blueprint mapped out by the CPV.
</P>
<P>
Phan Dien outlined his party's achievements in reforms and
economic construction since the Eighth Congress of the CPV, as
well as major measures his party had taken to overcome its current
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He said the Vietnamese government and the CPV attached great
importance to maintaining good neighborly relations and
cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Ex-CPV General-Secretary Do Muoi met with Chinese President
Jiang Zemin during his China tour last year, and reached consensus
on some major issues, which could serve as guidelines for the two
parties' relations into the 21st century, he said.
</P>
<P>
Phan Dien noted that two parties should enhance mutual
understanding, support each other and steadily push forward
economic relations. 
