<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Economy Expands in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Italian economy began expanding
again last year, but the growth failed to revive the employment
situation, according to the government's 1997 economic report.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth last year, when gross domestic product (GDP)
grew by just under two percent, was driven by a 2.4 percent
increase in private demand and a general increase in disposable
family incomes, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But the recovery in business and industry failed to produce an
upturn in employment, which fell by 0.2 percent. The overall
jobless rate was put at 12.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Investment rose by 0.6 percent, which showed that short-term
prospects for job creation were modest. The only area where
investment took off strongly in 1997 was in intermediary goods,
the report said, indicating that most new jobs will probably be
confined to service industries.
</P>
<P>
Investment in the construction industry fell sharply,
reflecting the crisis in the house-building sector, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rising international demand and a strong U.S. dollar
boosted Italian exports, which grew by 6.3 percent. The rise
however failed to counterbalance "the exceptional expansion in
imports," which soared by 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government attributed the import boom to automobile buying
and industry's need to stock up on new materials.
</P>
<P>
Despite the sharp increase in purchase of foreign products, the
falling deficit in invisible earnings meant that the current
account balance slipped slightly to 3.2 percent of GDP, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Second Annual ESAF Loan for Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) announced Friday the approval of a 31 million U.S. dollar
loan for Guinea under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility
(ESAF).
</P>
<P>
The loan, the second annual loan under ESAF, is provided in
support of the government's economic program for 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
It is available in two equal semi-annual installments, the
first of which will be made available on April 15.
</P>
<P>
The main macroeconomic objectives of the 1998 program include
achieving a growth rate of five percent in gross domestic product
(GDP) real terms, bringing down inflation to about 3.5 percent and
containing the current account deficit at 7.7 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting member
countries that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments and to improve their growth
prospects.
</P>
<P>
Guinea joined the IMF in September 1963. Its quota is about 105
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals about 96 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
