<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Import More Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' rice imports for
1998 may reach as high as 1.5 million tons due to the lingering
effects of the El Nino weather phenomenon on the country's rice
farms, press reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
National Food Authority deputy administrator Gregorio Tan was
quoted as saying the food agency has standby authority from the
government to import up to 1.15 million tons of rice this year.
</P>
<P>
But Tan said his agency was still waiting for the April crop
survey of the Bureau of Agricultural Statistics to determine how
much more the government will need in terms of imports.
</P>
<P>
Due to the dry spell caused by El Nino which significantly
reduced farm yields and plantings, the rice supply shortfall can
reach anywhere between 1.2 to 1.5 million tons, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Tan, the agency has already imported 500,000 tons
of rice, most of which came from Vietnam, followed by China and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The agency expects to bring in another 300,000 tons before the
start of the traditional lean rice supply period of July-September
in the country.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that rice stocks will be ample, the government will
make sure the national rice inventory by July 1 of every year is
good for 90 days supply.
</P>
<P>
But early indications reveal that to keep this ideal buffer
level, more than 1.15 million tons in imports will be needed, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The country's grain production for the first semester of 1998
is expected to fall by more than 12 percent due to the drought, it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
