<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Finance Chief Vows to Maintain High Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Interest rates of Thailand's banks
will remain high until the basic economic problems of the country
are solved and liquidity pressure eased, Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda said.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's Bangkok Post quoted the minister as saying that
foreign investors would see any effort to force interest rate cuts
as unwise until economic fundamentals improved.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after Bangkok bank, the country's largest
bank, announced on Thursday that it was raising lending interest
rates by 25-75 basis points.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank's move reflected continued tight liquidity in the
financial system, Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
Authorities have maintained that interest rates could drop only
when the baht stabilizes and capital inflows improve through a
revival of investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the baht traded at 40.7 against the dollar, bouncing
back after dropping as low as 41.2 earlier in the day. Dealers
said the weakness of the Japanese yen, which hit a seven-year low
against the dollar near 135, was pulling down the baht.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said the liquidation of the 56 closed finance firms,
recapitalization of other financial institutions and the takeover
of four troubled banks would help increase investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
Local bankers said fierce competition for deposits has also
caused interest rates to remain high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
