<HEADLINE> Minister of Civil Affairs Pledges Better Social Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Doje Cering, who was recently
re-appointed as minister of civil affairs, said yesterday that his
ministry will try to improve China's social environment to ensure
the reform, economic development and social stability.
</P>
<P>
The minister, from the Tibetan ethnic group, promised to take
responsibility for sharing the central government's cares for the
poor, reported today's "China Daily."
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to help people suffering from natural disasters
get over their difficulties by improving social welfare and
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
The minister said one of the most important tasks in his new
five-year term is to extend the scope of democracy at the
grassroots level to make sure that people directly exercise their
democratic rights.
</P>
<P>
People would manage their own affairs according to the law by
regulating the direct election of the village committees in rural
areas and neighbourhood committees in urban areas. Both of these
are self-management organizations.
</P>
<P>
The services the ministry provides go "from the cradle to the
grave," the minister said, referring to its administration over
citizens' birth, marriage and funeral service.
</P>
<P>
Doje Cering was confident that his ministry will continue to
play a key role in pressing ahead with the socialization of
China's welfare undertakings, particularly welfare services for an
ever-increasing number of senior citizens, more than 60 million
disabled people and other groups of urban and rural poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
