<HEADLINE> Philippines to Ask World Bank for Housing Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government plans to
borrow 1.14 billion U.S. dollars from the World Bank to set up
more socialized housing and at the same time develop the market
for secondary mortgage papers, a Philippine newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be on top of the 500 million dollar financial
sector adjustment loan the World Bank has committed to the
Philippines, the Malaya newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The development of secondary market for housing mortgage papers
will deepen the source of funding for mass housing.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines currently has a housing backlog in excess of
one million units.
</P>
<P>
The loan from the multilateral financing institution would be
used to establish institutions having the capability to create a
framework for private secondary mortgage institutions, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to provide the necessary legal reforms to
reduce the credit risk at a time when the cost of mortgage
takeouts have gone up.
</P>
<P>
This will also help address the complaints of property
developers of the high interest rates crippling the sector.
</P>
