<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Beef up Security Measures for World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- France will beef up anti-terrorism
measures to guarantee security during the World Cup finals this
summer, Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chevenement, at a two-day seminar of European police officers,
said France would "reinforce" the extraordinary measures put in
place after a spate of 1995 bombings which claimed eight people
with 160 others injuried.
</P>
<P>
The security measures included heavier police presence in train
and subway stations, public buildings and monuments. Trash cans
were either removed from city streets or sealed up and steel
barricades were set up outside schools.
</P>
<P>
Chevenement said that heavy penalties will be implemented
against "drunken behavior, introducing banned objects into
stadiums such as knives, or inciting racial hatred" during the
World Cup period.
</P>
<P>
Punishment for such offenses will include jail terms and bans
from attending matches in France for five years, the minister
said, adding a magistrate would be assigned to each stadium to
monitor arrests and assure swift judicial punishment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
