<HEADLINE> Minister Pledges Better Health Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- China's medical reform aims to ban
the practice of "lengthy prescription," a common practice enables
many hospitals to make money from medicine, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is also scheduled to gradually lower the cost of
medicines, the newly appointed Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, charges for technical services should be increased in
recognition of medical workers' skills, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister vows to improve service quality and efficiency by
reorganizing hospital design and facilities and improve
community-based health centers.
</P>
<P>
The final objective is to realize "the basic health for all,
and the sooner, the better," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that he is fully aware of the responsibilities
of his office because China's health reform and development lag
behind social and economic progress.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that he would study and work hard and try to
be a qualified health administrator, thus leaving a good
impression in the history of the country's health sector. 
</P>
