<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defending Champion Loses Two Singles in Davis Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Sweden suffered
a big blow by losing the first two singles in the first round of
the Davis Cup World Group on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Without three of its top players, Sweden fielded in Magnus
Norman and Mikael Tillstrom in the first day competition against
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
Dominik Hrbaty survived a protracted match to win over Norman,
who was battling the flu, 7-6 (7-5), 4-6, 6-4, 3-6, 6-2 while
Karol Kucera outwitted Tillstrom from a first set deficit 1-6,
6-1, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
The defeats were a shock for the defending champion but still
reasonable as Swedish Jonas Bjorkman and Thomas Enqvist were
absent with injuries while doubles specialist Nicklas Kulti
skipped the tournament to accompany his wife who just gave birth.
</P>
<P>
Hrbaty took 3 hours 20 minutes to take his match, pacing the
Slovaks for a great chance to qualify for the second round as the
doubles will reel off on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Led by former star Miloslav Mecir, who is currently captain,
Slovakia has won 11 of its 12 Davis Cup matches to progress
quickly in five years from the bottom ranks to the World Group,
the top 16 of Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
In Saturday doubles, Kucera and Jan Kroslak were expected to
team against Sweden's Magnus Larsson and Tillstrom.
</P>
<P>
On their home turf, two Davis Cup rookies gave Germany a 2-0
lead over South Africa in opening singles.
</P>
<P>
Nicolas Kiefer overcame a two-set deficit in his Davis Cup
debut for a 4-6, 4-6, 6-1, 6-2, 6-2 victory over Grant Stafford
before Tommy Haas celebrated his 20th birthday by upsetting Wayne
Ferreira 7-6 (7-2), 3-6, 6-3, 6-4 to put the Germans one victory
away from the second round.
</P>
<P>
The match also marked the debut of Boris Becker as Germany's
Davis Cup team boss. Becker was in semi retirement but might play
the doubles on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In Australia, Zimbabwe's Byron Black toppled U.S. Open champion
Pat Rafter to level the tie against Australia at 1-1. Black
bounced back to defeat fourth-ranked Rafter 3-6, 6-3, 6-2, 7-6
(7-0).
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Australia's Jason Stoltenberg beat Wayne Black in the
opening set 6-3, 6-4, 5-7, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, Jan Siemerink gave the Netherlands a 1-0 lead over
Belgium by beating Johan Van Herck 6-4, 6-3, 4-6, 6-1, while the
game between Belgium's No. 1 Filip De Wulf and Dutchman Sjeng
Schalken was postponed to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In Genoa, Italy took 1-0 lead over India as rain curbed Mahesh
Bhupathi's efforts to level the score. India's No.1 player was
leading Davis Cup debutante Davide Sanguinetti 6-2, 6-2, 2-3 when
the match was rained out.
</P>
<P>
Andrea Gaudenzi gave Italy its 1-0 with a 6-0, 6-2, 1-6, 6-2
victory against Prahland Srinath, making his Davis Cup debut.
</P>
<P>
In Zurich, Switzerland and the Czech Republic finished 1-1 as
Bohdan Ulihrach beat Switzerland's Ivo Heuberger 6-7 (8-6), 6-0,
7-5, 6-2 and Marc Rosset rebounded to beat Daniel Vacek 3-6, 6-2,
7-6 (7-5), 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten gave the home crowd a scare before he
rallied to defeat Spain's Carlos Moya 5-7, 1-6, 6-4, 6-4, 6-4.
Yet, his teammate Fernando Meligeni was defeated by Alex Corretja
of Spain 4-6, 6-4, 3-6, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
The matches between the United States and Russia were postponed
by rain with Jim Courier slated to play Yevgeny Kafelnikov and
Andre Agassi facing Andrei Olhovskiy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
