<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central America Seeks Rapprochement With Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Central American countries will
sign a commercial framework agreement with South America's largest
trade bloc, Mercosur, to seek closer ties between the two regions,
sources in the Costa Rican Foreign Trade Ministry said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The involved parties had planned to sign the agreement on April
17 in Buenos Aires, Argentina, before the Hemispheric Summit that
will be held in Santiago, Chile, on April 18 and 19.
</P>
<P>
However, the countries are considering to postpone the signing
until April 21.
</P>
<P>
The Central American countries started a rapprochement with
Mercosur, also known as the South American Common Market that
groups Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay, during their
negotiations for the creation of the Free Trade Area of the
Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
Talks on the FTAA will be officially launched during the
Santiago summit, after three years of preparatory conversations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
