<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 23 Percent of US Homes Online by 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 3 (Xinhua) -- By the end of this year, 23
percent of all U.S. households will be accesssing the Internet and
other online services, according to a new study of International
Data Corporation (IDC), a leading American provider of information
technology data, analysis and consulting.
</P>
<P>
DIC analysts also expect home users to catch up business users
when it comes to sophistication about use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Online and Internet usage in the home has increased dramatically
over the past 18 months, according to the IDC study. By the end of
1996, only about 13 percent of all U.S. households were online. The
current level is more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the increase in the number of users, both the
frequency of use and the amount of time spent online have also grown
significantly. Nearly 60 percent of all online households access their
online service at least once a day, increasing from only 35 percent
for the prior year.
</P>
<P>
Sub-PCs of 1,000 dollars and new devices like WebTV and digital
set-top boxes are partly contributed to the sharp increase.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that electronic commerce is even more
widespread among home users than business users, indicating that more
home users who are buying over the Web seem to feel comfortable with
Web-based payment mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Business users tend to purchase more expensive goods such as
airline tickets, hotel reservations, computer hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the availability of less expensive PCs and new Internet
devices, IDC cites World Wide Web content as a driver for increase
Internet access from home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Easy Passage" Put in Place Between Nicaragua, Honduras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua and Honduras have
started an "easy passage" system at their border post of El
Guasaule to speed up the processing of tourists, the Nicaraguan
Foreign Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The system is part of agreements reached by the CA-4 Group,
made up of Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador and Nicaragua, which
provide for a single point where migration and customs officers
work together to simplify the procedures for nationals and
passenger vehicles of the four countries.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles and their passengers of any of the CA-4 Group
countries will be granted a permit of stay of 90 days.
</P>
<P>
The CA-4 migration directors, who gathered in San Salvador
Wednesday, agreed to maintain open the border posts between the
four countries from 08:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m. local time).
</P>
<P>
But the El Guasaule border post will be open around the clock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Leads Belgians in Davis Cup Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Jan Siemerink entertained
hundreds of followers by winning the first of Friday's opening
singles of the Dutch-Belgian Davis Cup tie in the world group.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old, ranked 29th on the ATP tour, routed
71st-ranked Johan van Herck 6-4, 6-3, 4-6 and 6-1 in three hours,
though they had to wait for almost five hours for rain to stop and
match to start.
</P>
<P>
Siemerink, finalist of last month's Rotterdam championship and
semi-finalist at the London and Copenhagen open, proved simply too
much for Van Herck even though the Dutchman played stronger on
faster courts.
</P>
<P>
But Siemerink seemed to have little problem with the slow clay
court in Brussels and with the humidity by unleashing powerful
winning serves and demonstrating fleet-footedness.
</P>
<P>
The second of the day's opening singles between Sjeng Schalken
of the Netherlands and Filip Dewulf of Belgium had to be put off
for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands and Belgium met four times previously in the
Davis Cup, each winning two encounters. The Dutch whitewashed the
Belgians in their last Davis Cup tie in 1994. 
</P>
