<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian Wanda, Pohang Enter AFC Championship Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China's national first division
league champion Dalian Wanda and defending champion Pohang
Steelers of South Korea qualified for the final after winning
their semi-final matches at the 17th Asian Football Confederation
(AFC) Club Championships Finals here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wanda, three-time and defending national league champion, won
over last year's AFC Club Championship runner-up Pirouzi from Iran
2-0 in Friday's first semi-final.
</P>
<P>
Wanda is to take on Pohang Steelers, who beat last year's Asian
 Super Cup winner Al-Hilal from Saudi Arabia in the championship
final, set for Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
If Wanda wins over Pohang Steelers on Sunday, it would be
China's second triumph at the annual tournament, following the
victory in 1989 by China's Liaoning provincial team. The city of
Dalian is in the Northeastern Chinese province.
</P>
<P>
Pohang Steelers beat Al-Hilal 1-0 in Friday's second
semi-final.
</P>
<P>
Al-Hilal will meet Pirouzi in the third-place play-off prior to
the championship final Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Wanda's first goal in the Friday semi-final came in the 32nd
minute of the first half, when forward Wang Tao opened the score
with a slam shot within the goal area after receiving a pass from
teammate and national team member Hao Haidong.
</P>
<P>
Hao made it two for Wanda when he scored with a short-range
shot 64 minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
The veteran Chinese national team player was later named the
most valuable player of the match.
</P>
<P>
Pohang Steelers scored the sole goal of the game at the 45th
minute, through the efforts by Park Tae Ha, who was assisted by
teammate Hwang Sun Hong in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Much more physically fit, the Saudis launched wave upon wave of
offensives in the second half, with numerous threatening shots.
</P>
<P>
The match would have gone the very other way if not for the
tremendous efforts by Pohang's goalkeeper Kim Lee Sup, who
retrieved many dangerous shots from the swift and aggressive Saudi
forwards.
</P>
<P>
The four sides for the Hong Kong championship came out of a
qualifying tournament some four months long involving 15 teams
from West and Central Asia and 16 squads from East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The AFC Club Championships have been held annually since 1967,
except for 1969 and 1972-1984. Club sides from Israel, Iran and
South Korea each won three championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
