<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Department Reject Lawmaker's Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The State Department on Friday
rejected a demand by Benjamin Gilman, a key Republican
Representative, that President Bill Clinton make a decision within
three weeks on whether foreign companies are violating a U.S. law
prohibiting large investments in Iran's energy sector and whether
sanctions should be imposed against the companies as a result.
</P>
<P>
"All options available remain open, including the possibility
of sanctions," State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to speculate as to when our review will be
complete, but it certainly wouldn't be based on some arbitrary
deadline," he added.
</P>
<P>
Gilman, the chairman of the House International Relations
Committee sent a letter on Thursday to Clinton, saying his panel
will decide whether the White House is skirting the law if the
Clinton administration does not act three weeks later when
Congress reconvene after a recess.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. President, refusing to enforce the law in this case is not
an option, not least because your oath of office requires you to
see that the laws are faithfully executed," Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
"Congress is about to begin a three week recess. If (the law)
remains unimplemented when we reconvene, this committee will begin
to explore whether there has been a willful decision to not
enforce the law i this matters," he added.
</P>
<P>
Since late last year, the U.S. State Department has been
reviewing whether a 2 billion U.S. dollar deal by France's Total,
Russia's Gazprom and Malaysia's Petronas to develop a major
Iranian gas field violates a U.S. law that seeks to punish
companies investing 20 million or more U.S. dollars in Iran's or
Libya's energy sector over a 12-month period.
</P>
<P>
The State Department has also been reviewing whether a separate
$180 million deal in Iran's energy sector by Indonesia's Bakrie
Minorak Petroleum and Canada's Bow Valley Energy Ltd violates the
law.
</P>
<P>
Gilman criticized the administration for taking too long to
render a decision in either case and said "Congress cannot be
indifferent to whether the laws it passes are enforced."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said U.S. policy is being pursued under the law but that
the administration is examining what he called new factors,
including whether the Asia financial crisis is having as impact on
the investment.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. law against foreign companies investing in Iran's
energy sector has been criticized worldwide, especially by U.S.
allies, which rejected the law as interfering into other
countries' affairs.
</P>
<P>
They have vowed to retaliate if the United States enforce the
law and punish their firms.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has delayed to make a decision
whether to punish those foreign companies for fear of backfire
its action could ensue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
