<HEADLINE> Quebec Liberals Lead in Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Liberal Party of Quebec would
win the next provincial election with Jean Charest as their
leader, the latest poll suggests.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of Quebecers -- 49.7 percent -- would vote for the
Liberals if an election were held now, according to the poll by
the SOM firm for The Gazette and Le Soleil newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Only 30.7 percent of respondents said they would vote for the
ruling Parti Quebecois, whose leader Lucien Bouchard promised to
hold another sovereignty referendum if he wins.
</P>
<P>
With the undecided votes factored in, the poll showed, the
results of the election would have been 57.5 percent for the
Liberals, 35.5 percent for the Parti Quebecois, and 7.1 percent
for other parties.
</P>
<P>
The poll is the first taken since Charest announced last week
his intention to seek the Liberal leadership after Daniel Johnson
said he would step down to give his party a better chance to win
the next election, which must be held by autumn 1999.
</P>
<P>
Charest officially resigned on Friday as leader of the federal
Progressive Conservative Party after he bid farewell in the House
of Commons on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pollsers attributed the strong support for the pro-unity
Liberals largely to the fact that its potential leader Charest is
benefiting from enormous media attention around his jump into
Quebec politics.
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that Charest leads Bouchard in all age
groups except those under 25 years old in the French-speaking
province of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
