<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Net Wealth Grows in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada's national net worth rose
3.6 percent to 2.7 trillion dollars (1.9 trillion USD) in 1997,
reaching 87,100 per capita, Statistics Canada reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This was the result of an increase in national wealth, less a
small rise in Canada's net foreign indebtedness," the statistics
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Canada's national wealth rose 3.5 percent to 3 trillion
dollars, in line with an increase in domestic expenditures in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The gain resulted from acquisitions and revaluations of
tangible assets such as automobiles, houses, household
furnishings, appliances, land, business machinery and equipment,
office buildings, manufacturing plants and refineries.
</P>
<P>
"The change in wealth was broadly based in that all assets
grew, though at different rates," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Individuals accounted for 49 percent of national wealth,
unchanged from 1996.
</P>
<P>
National wealth grew almost 4.0 percent in both the personal
and corporate sectors, compared with a modest 1.4 percent in the
government sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
