<HEADLINE> WEU Military Chiefs to Meet in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The chiefs of staff of the West
European Union (WEU) will gather in the Greek capital city of
Athens next Monday to discuss the upgrading of the organization's
operational capacity.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference will be attended by the WEU's Secretary-
General Jose Cutileiro, chiefs of staff of the WEU, military
representatives of the 10 full members, the three associate
members, the five observer states as well as the WEU's planning
department director, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA)
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the participants will also discuss
issues concerning the future role and duties of the WEU's planning
department, participation of associate members in the meetings of
the military representatives group and the WEU's military
exercises doctrine.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Greece holds the WEU's rotating six-month
presidency.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, the WEU's ministerial meeting will take place
in the Greek island of Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1955, the WEU has 10 members which consist of
Belgium, France, Germany, Greece, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Portugal, Spain and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The WEU also has three associate members that include Iceland,
Norway, Turkey, five observers made up of Austria, Denmark,
Finland, Ireland and Sweden, 10 associate partners from Bulgaria,
the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland,
Romania, Slovakia and Slovenia. 
</P>
