<HEADLINE> Canada to Participate in UN African Peacekeeping, Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy announced Friday that Canada will take part in a
United Nations peacekeeping operation in the Central African
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Requested by the UN, Canada will send approximately 45 Canadian
Forces personnel to provide the communications element for the
mission, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the UN Security Council on March 27, the mission is
the first new UN peacekeeping operation in two years, and the
first in Africa in four years.
</P>
<P>
The UN will deploy up to 1,350 soldiers, civilian police and
officials in the African country, beginning from April 15.
</P>
<P>
Its mandate is mainly to assist the government of the Central
African Republic in maintaining security in and around the capital
city of Bangui.
</P>
<P>
It will also be responsible for ensuring the safety of UN
personnel, providing police training and disposing of the
surrendered weapons of demobilizing factions.
</P>
<P>
Other countries, including Burkina Faso, Chad, Cote d'Ivoire,
France, Gabon, Ghana, Mail, Senegal and Togo, also contribute
military contingents to the peacekeeping operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
