<HEADLINE> U.S. Believes Israel's Denial on Hamas Man's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Friday that it believed Israel had nothing to do with the death of
a Hamas bomb-maker.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told a briefing that as
Washington had no independent information on the case, "I'm not
aware of any reason to doubt" Israel's denial.
</P>
<P>
The bombmaker, Muhyideen al-Sharif, was found dead on Sunday
near a booby-trapped car in the West Bank town of Ramallah. He was
said to be shot dead.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Legislative Council said on Thursday that the
death of Sharif was a "criminal act" perpetrated by Israel. Hamas
has vowed to take revenge.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said on Friday that
Israel had nothing to do with Sharif's death.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States obviously believed what Netanyahu
had said.
</P>
<P>
"We obviously take Prime Minister Netanyahu at his word," he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also deplored threats of revenge by Hamas, saying: "We
deplore the statements of those Hamas officials who are trying to
use this event as an excuse advocate violence." 
</P>
