<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Rapporteur to Visit Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The newly appointed Special
Rapporteur of the United Nations Commission on Human Rights, Jiri
Dienstbier, will visit Belgrade on April 5, 1998, U.N. spokesman
Juan Carlos Brandt said Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is his first official visit to the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia since he was appointed on March 13 to replace Mrs
Elisabeth Rehn, and he is making the trip at the request of the
Commission of Human Rights, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Dienstbier, a former minister of foreign affairs of
Czechoslovakia from 1989-1992, will meet with Minister of Foreign
Affairs Zivadin Jovanovic and other governmental officials Monday.
</P>
<P>
Then he will travel to Pristina, where he will meet Tuesday
with governmental officials as well as representatives of Kosovan
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Dienstbier will make a preliminary report on his findings to
the Commission on Human Rights, which is now meeting in Geneva,
Carlos added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said this is the first part of a comprehensive
mission by the new Special Rapporteur and he receives the support
of the Office of the High commissioner for Human Rights which has
an office in Belgrade. 
