<DOCNO> XIE19980404.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forty Students Arrested to Curb Campus Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- South African police Friday
fired teargas and rubber bullets and arrested at least 40
students to curb riots on the campus of the University of
Transkei (Unitra) at Umtata in Eastern Cape province, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Police were called in when about 400 students toyi-toyed
(danced in traditional way ) and blocked entrances to the
university.
</P>
<P>
Police vehicles were stoned, police spokesman Wayne Hackart
said. "The situation is tense. Police have fired a lot of rubber
bullets and a lot of teargas," he added
</P>
<P>
The arrested 40 would be charged with public violence, said
Hackart.
</P>
<P>
Unitra public relations manager, Karuna Gopal, said the
students were part of a group given until Friday to pay
outstanding tuition fees. But she denied there were riots on the
campus.
</P>
<P>
"We have about 4,600 registered students who paid their fees.
Those who have not yet paid were given until today to pay. They
are now protesting but there are no riots at Unitra."
</P>
<P>
Unrest flared on the university's campus Monday when the
university announced that students who owed money would be
refused entry.
</P>
<P>
Students' failure to pay tuition fees plunged many
universities of South Africa into financial crisis and even
forced the Fort Hare University to shut down for a certain period
earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
